00:01:18.940 --> 00:01:21.790
I'm going to tell you a
little bit about my work

00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:25.180
and what we know about how
innovation actually produces

00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:27.059
value and destroys value.

00:01:27.059 --> 00:01:29.350
To do that, it's going to be
like an old Western movie,

00:01:29.350 --> 00:01:31.900
where we're going to
start with the long shot

00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:33.310
of the City of Dodge.

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:35.830
And then we're going to move
into the tumbleweed street.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:38.530
Then finally, we're going to
look at the sheriff, right?

00:01:38.530 --> 00:01:40.750
We're going to talk about you.

00:01:40.750 --> 00:01:44.290
So I want to start with
a little back story here.

00:01:44.290 --> 00:01:45.790
Both Staney and I
are technologists.

00:01:45.790 --> 00:01:47.081
We're trained as technologists.

00:01:47.081 --> 00:01:48.940
That's what our
advanced degrees are in.

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:51.400
But interestingly
enough, whenever

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:53.562
I'm anywhere in an airport,
and I travel a lot,

00:01:53.562 --> 00:01:55.270
somebody always wants
to stop and tell me

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:56.550
about new technology.

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:58.380
Hey, have you heard
about the latest thing?

00:01:58.380 --> 00:02:00.340
And I'm sure you guys
get this all the time.

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.580
And it's-- some of it's
apocryphal, that we're being--

00:02:03.580 --> 00:02:05.830
our technology's
coming from aliens.

00:02:05.830 --> 00:02:08.509
And some of it's stuff
that you've already seen

00:02:08.509 --> 00:02:09.979
and you already know.

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:11.939
But you all know that
technology happens.

00:02:11.939 --> 00:02:14.230
And the cycle of technology,
the magnitude and momentum

00:02:14.230 --> 00:02:16.806
of technology, always
increases over time.

00:02:16.806 --> 00:02:18.430
And there's a bunch
of laws about this.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:19.760
I won't bore you with that.

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:24.790
But around the late '80s,
I got a call from an editor

00:02:24.790 --> 00:02:25.990
at "Life" magazine.

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:29.210
And she wanted to talk
to me about innovation.

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:30.807
So I thought she
wanted to talk to me.

00:02:30.807 --> 00:02:32.890
And she said, no, I want
you to give a commentary.

00:02:32.890 --> 00:02:35.740
We're writing a piece on the
100 most important people

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:37.420
of the 20th century.

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:39.280
And one of them
is related to you.

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.150
Now, this was a huge surprise.

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:43.810
I don't know any-- most
people related to me--

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:45.820
not doing so well, right?

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:47.730
So there-- she
talked about this man

00:02:47.730 --> 00:02:49.750
named Charles Fair de Graff.

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:50.750
And she sort of--

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:51.920
I was embarrassed.

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:54.400
I didn't know who
this person was.

00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:55.690
Nobody told me about him.

00:02:55.690 --> 00:02:58.480
So when she got off the
phone, I looked him up.

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:00.700
And he was the guy who
created Pocket Books.

00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:03.310
He create paperback
books in the 1930s.

00:03:03.310 --> 00:03:06.100
And his whole idea
with this technology

00:03:06.100 --> 00:03:08.290
was that people would
become literate.

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:11.410
If books were cheap, 2 bits,
people would become literate,

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:12.436
but they didn't.

00:03:12.436 --> 00:03:13.810
And the reason it
stuck with me--

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:16.810
I was doing a project with
Alan Kay and Steve Jobs

00:03:16.810 --> 00:03:19.180
in the state of California
to try and develop

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:23.410
literacy for people
who were under-served.

00:03:23.410 --> 00:03:25.120
And we had the
exact same result.

00:03:25.120 --> 00:03:28.330
We didn't get any results
from introducing technology

00:03:28.330 --> 00:03:29.770
into the situation.

00:03:29.770 --> 00:03:33.130
And so very early on, that
began to galvanize my thoughts

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:36.640
about culture and the role of
culture and technology and how,

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:40.730
in some ways, culture overtakes
or co-opts technology.

00:03:40.730 --> 00:03:42.310
So what I want to
talk about today

00:03:42.310 --> 00:03:44.590
is that innovation isn't
really an invention.

00:03:44.590 --> 00:03:46.030
It's not just a gadget.

00:03:46.030 --> 00:03:48.070
It's not next-- the cool thing.

00:03:48.070 --> 00:03:51.730
It actually has a lot to do
with identifying patterns,

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:54.040
how those patterns go
together, identifying

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:56.630
how culture and competency
interact with those patterns.

00:03:56.630 --> 00:03:58.489
And I want to give
some examples of that.

00:03:58.489 --> 00:04:01.030
But I want to start with this
whole notion of dominant logic.

00:04:01.030 --> 00:04:03.070
And it's a really
big thing for Google.

00:04:03.070 --> 00:04:05.890
And you're getting a lot of
sort of press, negative press,

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:07.030
about this.

00:04:07.030 --> 00:04:09.760
And that is one of the things
that goes on in our world--

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:12.520
we sometimes call this in
business microsegmentation.

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:14.920
The notion is we have
a tendency to identify

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.019
and value people who
are like us, right?

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:19.224
That's kind of one of
the big challenges.

00:04:19.224 --> 00:04:20.890
And when social media
started, I started

00:04:20.890 --> 00:04:23.720
writing articles that got a
lot of negative attention,

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:26.710
saying that I wasn't sure
that social media was really

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:29.540
creating this kind of inclusive
society, that, in some ways,

00:04:29.540 --> 00:04:30.970
it was microsegmenting us.

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:32.592
The people who are
your friends, even

00:04:32.592 --> 00:04:35.050
though they may look different
and they may seem different,

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:37.930
they actually believe all the
same nonsense you believe.

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:40.570
And if they don't believe
it, what do you do?

00:04:40.570 --> 00:04:42.970
On a dark night, on a dark
road, you unfriend them.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:45.710
The Spanish Inquisition
couldn't have thought of this.

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:48.057
So the notion is we get
these very vertical segments.

00:04:48.057 --> 00:04:50.140
So if you've ever talked
to anybody about religion

00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:52.360
or politics, you know what
I mean by the whole notion

00:04:52.360 --> 00:04:53.229
of dominant logic.

00:04:53.229 --> 00:04:55.270
And it comes back to what
that crazy philosopher,

00:04:55.270 --> 00:04:57.700
Schopenhauer, said
over a century ago.

00:04:57.700 --> 00:05:00.100
"Every man," every
person, "takes the limits

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:02.644
of his own field of vision
for the limits of the world."

00:05:02.644 --> 00:05:04.060
And that's kind
of where we're at.

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:05.934
Now, I'm going to make
the argument that this

00:05:05.934 --> 00:05:07.940
is the problem of
modernity, and there's

00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:09.930
a way to solve this,
to get over this.

00:05:09.930 --> 00:05:12.710
So the key is how do we get
beyond this dominant logic?

00:05:12.710 --> 00:05:15.885
How do we develop a mindset
to actually be more inclusive?

00:05:15.885 --> 00:05:18.260
And I'm going to talk about
inclusiveness in a way that's

00:05:18.260 --> 00:05:20.635
very different than you've
probably heard it because it's

00:05:20.635 --> 00:05:21.850
not just politically correct.

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:23.100
It's not just morally correct.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:24.380
It's essential for innovation.

00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:25.588
I'm going to prove it to you.

00:05:25.588 --> 00:05:27.950
Now, it turns out that
every organization

00:05:27.950 --> 00:05:29.030
has to do two things.

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:31.380
And boy, Google, this is
really relevant to you.

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.010
The first thing an organization
has to do is maintain itself.

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:37.910
It has to produce
predictable outcomes.

00:05:37.910 --> 00:05:40.460
This is why capitalism
requires capitalists.

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:43.250
Whether you're a private equity,
whether you're publicly traded,

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:44.660
somebody has to show
that you're going

00:05:44.660 --> 00:05:45.951
to do things on a normal basis.

00:05:45.951 --> 00:05:49.160
And the way that that happens
is we get rid of variance.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:50.600
We create standards.

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:52.520
We call this operating
rhythm, right?

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:55.640
Now, the notion is that
makes us all predictable.

00:05:55.640 --> 00:05:59.820
But the problem is, just
like people, we want to grow.

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:02.570
So to grow, instead of
eliminating deviance,

00:06:02.570 --> 00:06:05.390
what we need to do
is introduce it.

00:06:05.390 --> 00:06:08.134
So innovation, by definition,
is a form of deviance.

00:06:08.134 --> 00:06:09.800
And so we're going
to have this tension.

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:12.920
And it's not a tension of type.

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:14.240
It's not, I'm an ENTP.

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:15.650
You're an INFJ.

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:17.060
It's not that.

00:06:17.060 --> 00:06:22.010
It's one form of value actually,
literally, assaults the other.

00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:23.750
One form of value
destroys the other.

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:25.970
I want you to think about
high-growth economies

00:06:25.970 --> 00:06:28.340
versus high-quality or
productive economies.

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:29.280
They're oppositional.

00:06:29.280 --> 00:06:30.200
And there's a reason.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:31.790
One is creating standards.

00:06:31.790 --> 00:06:33.260
And one is creating deviance.

00:06:33.260 --> 00:06:35.093
Now, I'm going to say
something that's going

00:06:35.093 --> 00:06:36.530
to seem very radical to you.

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:40.010
This tension, when
used properly,

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:43.970
is actually not only good, it's
the basis of the growth engine.

00:06:43.970 --> 00:06:46.370
So let me give some
examples of culture

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:48.829
and how culture
co-opts technology.

00:06:48.829 --> 00:06:50.870
Interestingly enough,
everyone talks about Tesla.

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:52.036
And it's a great technology.

00:06:52.036 --> 00:06:53.270
And I love Tesla.

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:54.440
But here's the problem.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:57.170
Tesla last year
sold 55,000 cars.

00:06:57.170 --> 00:06:58.340
And they lost $600 million.

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.990
Now, they're not going to lose
$600 million going forward.

00:07:00.990 --> 00:07:03.290
And they're going to sell
maybe twice as many cars.

00:07:03.290 --> 00:07:06.140
But the notion is we've had some
soft quarters in the automobile

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:07.370
industry, haven't we?

00:07:07.370 --> 00:07:10.850
Tesla hasn't destroyed the
automobile industry, right?

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:13.219
What's affecting the
automobile industry is Uber.

00:07:13.219 --> 00:07:15.260
Now, I want you to think
about Uber for a minute.

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:16.551
Where's the innovation in Uber?

00:07:16.551 --> 00:07:17.270
Ride sharing.

00:07:17.270 --> 00:07:18.290
I'm an old guy.

00:07:18.290 --> 00:07:20.112
We had ride sharing
when I was a kid.

00:07:20.112 --> 00:07:21.320
You called the parish priest.

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.194
You called the coach.

00:07:22.194 --> 00:07:23.270
You got a ride.

00:07:23.270 --> 00:07:25.040
Look at the app that they use.

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:28.370
Doesn't it look like 2007,
over-the-road, trucking app?

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:30.227
It's not a particularly
well-run company.

00:07:30.227 --> 00:07:32.060
There's all kinds of
legal problems with it.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:34.400
Where's the innovation in Uber?

00:07:34.400 --> 00:07:38.820
Young people like you will get
in the car with a stranger,

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:39.320
right?

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:41.120
It's a social innovation.

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:42.110
I won't.

00:07:42.110 --> 00:07:43.760
It's like Airbnb.

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:46.310
All of the sudden, the car is
not just something you drive.

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:47.768
It's something you
take someone in.

00:07:47.768 --> 00:07:49.940
Airbnb-- if someone
came to my house--

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:52.710
I have a nice house on the
Huron River-- and use my towel,

00:07:52.710 --> 00:07:54.710
I take it in the backyard,
burn it, and bury it.

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:56.540
I'd sic the dogs on them, right?

00:07:56.540 --> 00:07:59.060
The notion is this
social form of innovation

00:07:59.060 --> 00:08:00.440
has co-opted this.

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:02.330
Same is true for Goldman Sachs.

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:04.580
Anybody remember about four
years ago-- not even four,

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:06.680
three years ago-- the number one
selling book on "The New York

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:08.034
Times" nonfiction book was--

00:08:08.034 --> 00:08:09.950
nonfiction list was a
book called "Flash Boys"

00:08:09.950 --> 00:08:10.820
by Michael Lewis.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:12.140
It was about Spread Networks.

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:14.450
The notion was Goldman
Sachs and Credit Suisse

00:08:14.450 --> 00:08:17.300
were trading a little faster
than you were-- could trade.

00:08:17.300 --> 00:08:19.250
So they got the
uplift on a stock.

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:21.120
And they got to sell,
get rid of the stock.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:23.360
They got to short the stock
as it started to go down.

00:08:23.360 --> 00:08:24.300
Now, think of it this way.

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:26.800
They're the bookie-- doesn't
matter whether Michigan or Ohio

00:08:26.800 --> 00:08:27.320
State wins.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:28.570
The bookie always makes money.

00:08:28.570 --> 00:08:29.900
That's what this deal was.

00:08:29.900 --> 00:08:31.400
And everyone said,
the fix is in.

00:08:31.400 --> 00:08:33.890
The 1% is going to get
richer and richer, until what

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:34.640
started happening?

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:36.340
Until cryptocurrency
started to come in.

00:08:36.340 --> 00:08:38.330
And that's what
you young people--

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:40.250
now, where did
cryptocurrency start?

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:41.990
And don't say the '98 paper.

00:08:41.990 --> 00:08:43.720
That's not where it started.

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:46.430
Where it really started
was in money laundering.

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:48.110
It started with drug cartels.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:49.630
Where did streaming
really start?

00:08:49.630 --> 00:08:52.130
I mean, in earnest, where did
that new technology come from?

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:53.180
The porn industry, right?

00:08:53.180 --> 00:08:54.290
Where did emojis start?

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:55.790
It started in terrorist cells.

00:08:55.790 --> 00:08:58.430
So one of the things I want
to point out right off the bat

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:02.300
is that technologies are often
used or first adapted by groups

00:09:02.300 --> 00:09:03.984
that they're not intended for.

00:09:03.984 --> 00:09:05.900
Anybody see the problem
happen in Amazon right

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:07.970
before Christmas, their
little recommendation

00:09:07.970 --> 00:09:09.200
engine, the little
problem that showed up

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:10.220
in "The New York Times"?

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:12.344
If you like fertilizer,
you might like black powder

00:09:12.344 --> 00:09:13.610
and ball bearings, right?

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:16.610
The notion is
technology is powerful.

00:09:16.610 --> 00:09:18.920
When we start looking at
people who are making these

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:20.670
smartphones, going
back a decade--

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:22.460
it's only been a decade--

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:24.170
in their wildest
dreams, they never

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:25.760
imagined that you
would use the camera

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:27.132
to take pictures of yourself.

00:09:27.132 --> 00:09:29.090
They thought you'd be at
Yellowstone and taking

00:09:29.090 --> 00:09:30.560
the vistas and things like that.

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:32.810
So culture has this
mitigating factor

00:09:32.810 --> 00:09:36.290
where what you want technology
to do is completely different.

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:39.020
And think about the 13
indictments two weeks ago

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:40.010
that Mueller has made.

00:09:40.010 --> 00:09:43.612
So the notion is this culture
piece is not only confounding,

00:09:43.612 --> 00:09:45.320
it actually does
something more powerful.

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:47.403
And the biggest industry
to look at for this right

00:09:47.403 --> 00:09:48.410
now is pharmaceuticals.

00:09:48.410 --> 00:09:50.540
The pharmaceutical
industry is reeling.

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:51.590
Why is it reeling?

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:53.990
Because all of these big
pharmaceutical companies

00:09:53.990 --> 00:09:56.330
are all of the sudden
having to compete

00:09:56.330 --> 00:09:58.490
with young people like
yourself who've got together

00:09:58.490 --> 00:10:00.170
in a federation deal.

00:10:00.170 --> 00:10:04.005
And they have names like
BIOS Forum and Firestorm

00:10:04.005 --> 00:10:04.880
and things like that.

00:10:04.880 --> 00:10:07.550
And what they're doing is
they're developing medications

00:10:07.550 --> 00:10:10.100
and therapies and drugs.

00:10:10.100 --> 00:10:12.860
And they're open source
patenting them, right?

00:10:12.860 --> 00:10:14.810
So the notion is--
here's the question.

00:10:14.810 --> 00:10:16.070
I was at Duke the other day.

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:17.540
And I was talking to the
head of their law school.

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:19.370
And I said, where are all
your lawyers going these days?

00:10:19.370 --> 00:10:21.500
Because it's tough to get
a job if you're a lawyer.

00:10:21.500 --> 00:10:22.670
And they said, pharmaceuticals.

00:10:22.670 --> 00:10:23.780
Well, the answer is simple.

00:10:23.780 --> 00:10:25.070
What are they doing
in pharmaceuticals?

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:26.960
They're trying to protect
their intellectual property.

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:28.440
Here becomes the
question for you.

00:10:28.440 --> 00:10:30.260
Who's going to win
this bar fight?

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:32.000
Is it going to be the
millions of people

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
who are trying to do things
for free in this open source,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:36.770
or is it going to
be a handful of sort

00:10:36.770 --> 00:10:38.690
of these very monopolistic
kind of companies

00:10:38.690 --> 00:10:40.680
that are trying to protect
the intellectual property?

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:42.554
That's why we're seeing
these companies start

00:10:42.554 --> 00:10:45.420
in places that don't have strong
intellectual property laws--

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:47.870
Tanzania, places like that,
parts of the Philippines,

00:10:47.870 --> 00:10:49.920
Cebu, other kinds of places.

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:52.010
So I want to take a step back.

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:55.209
So there's this big trend, this
trend towards technology coming

00:10:55.209 --> 00:10:57.500
out of places and people
doing different things with it

00:10:57.500 --> 00:11:00.230
because of culture, and
then this other big trend

00:11:00.230 --> 00:11:03.050
of the challenge between
organizations trying to control

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:06.800
things-- we're going to
call this longitude--

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:08.360
and organizations networking.

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:10.640
We're going to call
this latitude, longitude

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:12.440
and latitude of organizations.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:14.450
Well, how does
innovation actually

00:11:14.450 --> 00:11:15.990
relate to all this is--

00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:17.960
has to start with
what's our definition.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:20.330
About 1993, I got to
write the definition

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:22.310
for the federal
government for innovation.

00:11:22.310 --> 00:11:26.090
And all I did was co-opt
a very famous definition

00:11:26.090 --> 00:11:29.090
from innovation from the
1960s from Marshall McLuhan.

00:11:29.090 --> 00:11:31.520
McLuhan said innovation
has four attributes.

00:11:31.520 --> 00:11:34.020
He said, first of all, an
innovation enhances something.

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:35.480
Well, here we are at Google.

00:11:35.480 --> 00:11:37.160
Were you the first
search engine?

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:39.740
No.

00:11:39.740 --> 00:11:42.840
Did you have the same sort of
format as other search engines?

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:43.340
No.

00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:44.580
You had a little box.

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:46.220
And what Google
made better was not

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:48.200
so much it was a faster
search or a better

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:50.840
search at the beginning,
it was an easier search.

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:52.910
It was a simpler search, right?

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.047
So you made it better
by simplifying it.

00:11:55.047 --> 00:11:56.630
Now, the second thing
is an innovation

00:11:56.630 --> 00:11:58.910
has to eliminate something.

00:11:58.910 --> 00:12:01.070
What does the innovation kill?

00:12:01.070 --> 00:12:02.619
Now, that's a tough one, right?

00:12:02.619 --> 00:12:04.910
I want you to think about
what did Charles Schwab kill.

00:12:04.910 --> 00:12:06.860
Does anybody remember
brokerage houses,

00:12:06.860 --> 00:12:08.810
the big brokerage
houses in-- on Fifth Ave

00:12:08.810 --> 00:12:10.220
and down on Wall Street?

00:12:10.220 --> 00:12:11.810
They're all gone now.

00:12:11.810 --> 00:12:14.000
EF Hutton, the quiet
company is really quiet.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:14.750
Why?

00:12:14.750 --> 00:12:16.910
Because we disintermediated
the broker.

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:19.070
Basically, we let
trading happen directly.

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:21.444
Of course, this is an industry
you have a lot of interest

00:12:21.444 --> 00:12:23.420
in, a lot of stakes
in the ground here.

00:12:23.420 --> 00:12:25.610
It has to return
us to something.

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:27.300
Here's an interesting one.

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:31.100
It has to make us
feel like we're--

00:12:31.100 --> 00:12:33.220
do we need to do something here?

00:12:33.220 --> 00:12:33.720
We're OK?

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:34.780
All right.

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:38.540
It has to make us feel like
we're returning to something.

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:39.290
So think about it.

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:41.331
What are the big trends
in restaurants right now?

00:12:41.331 --> 00:12:45.100
Is it faster food, or is
it slow food, whole food,

00:12:45.100 --> 00:12:46.840
farm to table, right?

00:12:46.840 --> 00:12:49.660
And the ultimate, the ultimate
returning us to something

00:12:49.660 --> 00:12:52.330
we feel we lost, was
developed about two blocks

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:54.670
that direction,
which was Viagra--

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:56.180
we're 25 again.

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:59.020
And finally, the most
important thing McLuhan said,

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:01.220
and I've got your
little logo up here--

00:13:01.220 --> 00:13:02.920
the most important
thing McLuhan said--

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:05.470
he said, over time,
an innovation reverses

00:13:05.470 --> 00:13:07.780
into its opposite,
the anti-innovation.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:11.450
Does anybody remember when
email was going to set you free?

00:13:11.450 --> 00:13:12.370
Anybody remember that?

00:13:12.370 --> 00:13:12.670
Yeah.

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:13.270
And now what?

00:13:13.270 --> 00:13:14.534
We're all slaves, right?

00:13:14.534 --> 00:13:15.700
We can't put our phone down.

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:19.064
We're all slaves to email
and SMS and everything else.

00:13:19.064 --> 00:13:20.980
Now, I'm going to add a
few things to McLuhan.

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:25.210
Number one, innovation is
a form of useful novelty.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:27.220
All that means is it
can happen anywhere.

00:13:27.220 --> 00:13:28.720
Innovation can happen anywhere.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:30.886
So I want you to think about
Starbucks for a minute.

00:13:30.886 --> 00:13:31.870
It's a commodity.

00:13:31.870 --> 00:13:33.580
The Egyptians had it.

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:36.075
It's something that's been
around for 3,000 years.

00:13:36.075 --> 00:13:37.575
Where's the innovation
in Starbucks?

00:13:37.575 --> 00:13:38.800
Well, it's theater, right?

00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:40.290
It's the whole experience
of going to Starbucks.

00:13:40.290 --> 00:13:41.748
And they have names
for everything.

00:13:41.748 --> 00:13:43.300
Innovation pays in the future.

00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:45.340
It's what's called a
convex form of value.

00:13:45.340 --> 00:13:48.340
How much data do we have
on the future, anyone?

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:49.442
How much data?

00:13:49.442 --> 00:13:51.400
So I'm coming home from
Shanghai the other day.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:53.780
And this guy sitting next
to me says, the dollar--

00:13:53.780 --> 00:13:55.490
is it going up or down?

00:13:55.490 --> 00:13:56.682
I said, it's going down.

00:13:56.682 --> 00:13:57.890
He said, why do you say that?

00:13:57.890 --> 00:13:59.110
And I said, because it's up.

00:13:59.110 --> 00:14:00.359
And that's what currencies do.

00:14:00.359 --> 00:14:01.370
They go up and down.

00:14:01.370 --> 00:14:02.080
Duh.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:03.250
And he said what?

00:14:03.250 --> 00:14:04.840
He said, when?

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:06.160
I said, I don't know when.

00:14:06.160 --> 00:14:07.960
If I knew when, I'd
be George Soros.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:09.330
I'd be speculating the dollar.

00:14:09.330 --> 00:14:11.680
And I sure wouldn't be telling
a pathetic loser like you

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:14.030
about the dollar.

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:17.650
So the point is the biggest
form of resistance to innovation

00:14:17.650 --> 00:14:20.770
is excessive planning or getting
stuck in the planning cycle.

00:14:20.770 --> 00:14:22.970
Have you been to the
meeting about the meeting?

00:14:22.970 --> 00:14:25.210
Have you seen the
report about the report?

00:14:25.210 --> 00:14:26.010
Yeah.

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:27.010
You're the big guys now.

00:14:27.010 --> 00:14:28.710
You used to be the
small guys, right?

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.460
So someone else is running
experiment right now

00:14:30.460 --> 00:14:31.460
where you're doing that.

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:33.590
And finally, innovations
have a shelf life.

00:14:33.590 --> 00:14:34.640
They go sour like milk.

00:14:34.640 --> 00:14:36.040
So the other day,
I'm in Chicago.

00:14:36.040 --> 00:14:38.290
I'm giving the keynote speech
for the American Medical

00:14:38.290 --> 00:14:38.890
Association.

00:14:38.890 --> 00:14:40.348
I'm feeling pretty
good about this.

00:14:40.348 --> 00:14:41.800
It's a big meeting.

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:44.375
But I notice on Michigan Avenue,
the line goes all the way

00:14:44.375 --> 00:14:45.250
down Michigan Avenue.

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:47.000
And I'm thinking, holy mackerel.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.550
There's a lot of
people here hearing

00:14:48.550 --> 00:14:50.350
my silly talk about innovation.

00:14:50.350 --> 00:14:53.420
And then it occurs to me,
what's being released?

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:55.720
The new Apple iPhone
is being released.

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:58.180
And they're basically in
line to get the new iPhone.

00:14:58.180 --> 00:15:00.820
And of course, what happens
to the old iPhone the minute

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:02.800
the new iPhone is introduced?

00:15:02.800 --> 00:15:04.270
It's rubbish, right?

00:15:04.270 --> 00:15:07.190
It's discounted, falls
off the commodity cycle.

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:08.620
So the big challenge
of innovation

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:10.995
is it's only an innovation
for a moment in time.

00:15:10.995 --> 00:15:12.370
So this is what
an innovation is,

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:14.530
which means it can happen
in the supply chain,

00:15:14.530 --> 00:15:17.000
can happen in marketing, can
happen in the product itself.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.617
It's a lot more than the gadget.

00:15:18.617 --> 00:15:20.200
So there's other
mythologies, I think,

00:15:20.200 --> 00:15:21.400
that people have
about innovation

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:22.510
I wanted to dispel you of.

00:15:22.510 --> 00:15:24.310
First of all,
innovative organizations

00:15:24.310 --> 00:15:26.000
have very little in common.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.660
When we start looking at
the indexes for innovations,

00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:31.780
and there's about
seven that started--

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:33.339
there's about 13
legitimate ones now.

00:15:33.339 --> 00:15:34.630
There's hundreds of other ones.

00:15:34.630 --> 00:15:37.590
But let's say out of 13
ones, there's about 15%

00:15:37.590 --> 00:15:39.340
of the companies that
they have in common,

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:40.715
which tells you
right off the bat

00:15:40.715 --> 00:15:42.710
that they're not talking
about the same thing.

00:15:42.710 --> 00:15:45.430
Two, money is almost never
a barrier to innovation.

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:47.638
I don't know if you know
this-- one of the big issues

00:15:47.638 --> 00:15:50.069
is money often creates
a constraint when you

00:15:50.069 --> 00:15:51.610
have less money that
you have to have

00:15:51.610 --> 00:15:52.540
an interesting work-around.

00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:54.998
And we could talk about how
the economy is flush with money

00:15:54.998 --> 00:15:58.330
right now because the tax
cut and all the repatriation

00:15:58.330 --> 00:16:00.350
of the money is going
to put about a trillion,

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:02.412
maybe $2 trillion
back in this economy.

00:16:02.412 --> 00:16:04.870
So the notion is, is this really
going to go to innovation?

00:16:04.870 --> 00:16:06.490
Is it going to go
to stock buyback?

00:16:06.490 --> 00:16:08.259
Is it going to go
to private equity?

00:16:08.259 --> 00:16:09.550
Where is the money going to go?

00:16:09.550 --> 00:16:11.550
Competitors often
compete in opposite ways.

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:13.130
So this is one that
relates to you.

00:16:13.130 --> 00:16:14.838
Google, you have how
many companies now--

00:16:14.838 --> 00:16:16.510
58, 59 companies, right?

00:16:16.510 --> 00:16:17.660
You make everything.

00:16:17.660 --> 00:16:19.840
You're open source, man, right?

00:16:19.840 --> 00:16:22.000
Apple-- what, Apple makes what?

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:23.710
They make nothing, right?

00:16:23.710 --> 00:16:26.620
Foxconn and InvoTech and
a consortium of companies

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.070
make Apple's product.

00:16:28.070 --> 00:16:29.247
They make design.

00:16:29.247 --> 00:16:30.580
And they make brilliant designs.

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:32.190
You have to give that to Apple.

00:16:32.190 --> 00:16:34.731
And the other thing they make
is they make a closed operating

00:16:34.731 --> 00:16:35.470
system, right?

00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:37.810
In their ecosystem, it's not
just different than yours.

00:16:37.810 --> 00:16:39.700
It's almost oppositional, right?

00:16:39.700 --> 00:16:40.720
One's playing offense.

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:42.310
One's playing defense.

00:16:42.310 --> 00:16:44.824
So the whole idea that people,
even in the same kind of--

00:16:44.824 --> 00:16:47.240
in a Venn diagram-- you're not
in the exact same industry,

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:48.880
but in related industries--
compete the same way they

00:16:48.880 --> 00:16:49.420
don't.

00:16:49.420 --> 00:16:51.128
Incumbents are almost
never first movers.

00:16:51.128 --> 00:16:53.380
This is what you have to
worry about, Google, right?

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:54.520
Think about it as a bar fight.

00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:56.530
Anybody from a blue-collar
neighborhood, like I am?

00:16:56.530 --> 00:16:57.730
Anybody from a
blue-collar-- yeah,

00:16:57.730 --> 00:16:59.770
you're from the same
neighborhood I am, right?

00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:01.217
The notion is who
throws the-- is

00:17:01.217 --> 00:17:02.800
it the big guy with
a Budweiser jacket

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:05.079
or is it the little
guy with crazy eyes?

00:17:05.079 --> 00:17:06.790
It's the little guy.

00:17:06.790 --> 00:17:09.160
We call this in business
first-mover advantage.

00:17:09.160 --> 00:17:11.230
And this is why startups
throw the first punch,

00:17:11.230 --> 00:17:13.609
because they can't
compete on scope or scale.

00:17:13.609 --> 00:17:15.970
So when I start looking at
what's happened with Google,

00:17:15.970 --> 00:17:18.346
I think your cap value this
morning is like $680 billion.

00:17:18.346 --> 00:17:20.720
I think you're that second or
third most valuable company

00:17:20.720 --> 00:17:21.339
in the world.

00:17:21.339 --> 00:17:22.569
You're no longer a startup.

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:24.192
And the real challenge
here is what?

00:17:24.192 --> 00:17:25.900
Getting you to act
like you're a startup.

00:17:25.900 --> 00:17:28.180
I look at your new building,
your beautiful building.

00:17:28.180 --> 00:17:29.380
I see all the trappings.

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:31.030
Remember, I built
Domino's, I helped

00:17:31.030 --> 00:17:32.750
build Domino's in
the 1980s, which

00:17:32.750 --> 00:17:35.390
was the fastest-growing company
in the world in the 1980s.

00:17:35.390 --> 00:17:37.220
The interesting thing
is at some point,

00:17:37.220 --> 00:17:39.511
you're going to have that
real challenge of maintenance

00:17:39.511 --> 00:17:40.310
versus growth.

00:17:40.310 --> 00:17:42.080
It turns out that
breakthrough happens

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:43.130
at the edges of the bell curve.

00:17:43.130 --> 00:17:44.880
We'll talk about that
later because that's

00:17:44.880 --> 00:17:45.870
a very important point.

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:48.120
And this is a point that
Staney's going to talk about,

00:17:48.120 --> 00:17:52.070
which is when we started looking
at innovation indexes in 1993,

00:17:52.070 --> 00:17:54.770
less than 1% of them
on a regular basis

00:17:54.770 --> 00:17:56.960
beat the growth
benchmark on Wall Street.

00:17:56.960 --> 00:17:58.700
So the notion is most
of what you believe

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:00.414
about innovation is untrue.

00:18:00.414 --> 00:18:02.330
And we're going to talk
about why it's untrue.

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:03.996
There's only one thing
that we're pretty

00:18:03.996 --> 00:18:05.300
sure we know about innovation.

00:18:05.300 --> 00:18:07.883
And this is going to be the key
to the whole discussion today,

00:18:07.883 --> 00:18:10.700
and that is diversity happens
in the 30 to 50 places

00:18:10.700 --> 00:18:12.200
on the planet that
produce almost

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:13.450
all the intellectual property.

00:18:13.450 --> 00:18:15.741
And when we look at these
places, whether it's Tel Aviv

00:18:15.741 --> 00:18:17.270
or whether it's a
part of Shanghai,

00:18:17.270 --> 00:18:19.800
whether it's Ann Arbor, Michigan
or whether it's Palo Alto

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.269
or Cary, North Carolina,
wherever you're at,

00:18:22.269 --> 00:18:23.810
one of the things
you're going to see

00:18:23.810 --> 00:18:26.090
is it looks very
different than any place

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:29.155
if you drove 40 miles outside
of the city boundaries, right?

00:18:29.155 --> 00:18:31.780
And one of the things we see is
that people are very different.

00:18:31.780 --> 00:18:33.780
I'm going to talk about
why that's so important.

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:35.960
Now, remember the whole
idea that I started with,

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:38.418
talking about the magnitude of
innovation and the momentum,

00:18:38.418 --> 00:18:39.710
or the speed and magnitude.

00:18:39.710 --> 00:18:42.376
The two things you have to think
about is how much and how fast.

00:18:42.376 --> 00:18:44.820
That's the question you
always must ask yourself-- how

00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:46.070
much innovation, and how fast?

00:18:46.070 --> 00:18:47.777
Is a meteor careening
towards the earth?

00:18:47.777 --> 00:18:48.860
It's going to kill us all.

00:18:48.860 --> 00:18:50.120
We better do something now.

00:18:50.120 --> 00:18:52.514
Or is it that the
ice caps are melting,

00:18:52.514 --> 00:18:54.680
and we probably should do
something in the next four

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:57.290
or five years in order to get
our-- a handle on this, right?

00:18:57.290 --> 00:18:58.970
Maybe it's even a little
more urgent than that.

00:18:58.970 --> 00:18:59.600
Who knows?

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:01.670
But the first thing
that companies do

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:02.940
is they build a process.

00:19:02.940 --> 00:19:04.190
Now, here's a question to you.

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:07.520
Does process create deviance
or eliminate deviance?

00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:09.820
What does process do?

00:19:09.820 --> 00:19:11.140
It eliminates deviance.

00:19:11.140 --> 00:19:11.800
Yeah.

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:14.620
So the first thing we do to
make innovation happen is what?

00:19:14.620 --> 00:19:16.949
We build something to
eliminate innovation.

00:19:16.949 --> 00:19:18.740
And this is what we do
in business schools.

00:19:18.740 --> 00:19:19.652
This is stage-gating.

00:19:19.652 --> 00:19:20.860
This is portfolio management.

00:19:20.860 --> 00:19:22.120
These are hurdle rates.

00:19:22.120 --> 00:19:24.160
So the notion is we're
trying to gain control

00:19:24.160 --> 00:19:27.400
because what we really want
from innovation is what?

00:19:27.400 --> 00:19:29.830
We want predictable revenue.

00:19:29.830 --> 00:19:31.280
We want predictable things.

00:19:31.280 --> 00:19:33.072
So by definition, when
you build a process,

00:19:33.072 --> 00:19:35.571
you're going to be incremental
because that's what processes

00:19:35.571 --> 00:19:36.363
are designed to do.

00:19:36.363 --> 00:19:38.029
That's what that tool
is designed to do.

00:19:38.029 --> 00:19:40.090
Now, what if we really
wanted to do something

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:42.160
with much higher
magnitude for innovation?

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:44.020
Wouldn't we have to
change the gene pool?

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:46.840
It's like a great sports
team or an orchestra

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:48.310
or a band or a great chef.

00:19:48.310 --> 00:19:50.710
Wouldn't we have to go
out and get people, right?

00:19:50.710 --> 00:19:54.370
How long does it take to develop
a tremendous innovator here

00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:55.600
at Google?

00:19:55.600 --> 00:19:58.900
A long time-- or a professor
at Michigan or Stanford

00:19:58.900 --> 00:20:00.010
or Harvard, whoever you--

00:20:00.010 --> 00:20:01.718
wherever you came
from, wherever you are.

00:20:01.718 --> 00:20:03.910
So the notion is this
type of innovation's

00:20:03.910 --> 00:20:05.680
much higher but harder to do.

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:07.420
That's why Google
spends a lot of money

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:09.790
on you, developing you, because
that's really important.

00:20:09.790 --> 00:20:11.165
We do the same
thing at Michigan.

00:20:11.165 --> 00:20:13.060
Now, finally, if I
really, really want

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:15.160
to change culture,
what I-- if I really

00:20:15.160 --> 00:20:18.130
want to change the culture
to make innovation happen,

00:20:18.130 --> 00:20:20.552
is that going to
happen overnight?

00:20:20.552 --> 00:20:21.260
It takes forever.

00:20:21.260 --> 00:20:24.080
Now, I'm going to say something
that's really controversial.

00:20:24.080 --> 00:20:26.540
There's only two ways
to change culture,

00:20:26.540 --> 00:20:28.940
because culture isn't
a thing you can touch.

00:20:28.940 --> 00:20:30.580
Culture is in the ether.

00:20:30.580 --> 00:20:31.790
Culture is the way you talk.

00:20:31.790 --> 00:20:33.130
It's their mindset.

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:35.900
It's the way you interact.

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:37.302
It's not a thing.

00:20:37.302 --> 00:20:38.760
Culture is contained
in two things.

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:41.240
Number one, it's contained
in leadership, how you lead.

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:43.601
What do we do if you're
acquiring an underperforming

00:20:43.601 --> 00:20:44.100
firm?

00:20:44.100 --> 00:20:46.670
What is the first step when
you acquire an underperforming

00:20:46.670 --> 00:20:47.169
firm?

00:20:47.169 --> 00:20:48.390
You got it there, right?

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:49.600
Knuckle bump.

00:20:49.600 --> 00:20:51.560
You get rid of the senior suite.

00:20:51.560 --> 00:20:53.180
The Chinese have a
wonderful saying.

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:54.587
The fish stinks from the head.

00:20:54.587 --> 00:20:56.420
They have a wonderful
saying for everything.

00:20:56.420 --> 00:20:57.886
But that's what that means.

00:20:57.886 --> 00:20:59.510
That means you got
to get rid of people

00:20:59.510 --> 00:21:01.650
because culture is
contained in leadership.

00:21:01.650 --> 00:21:03.950
And if you got great leaders,
you get golden handcuffs.

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:06.030
Oh, they're going to stay
for two or three years.

00:21:06.030 --> 00:21:08.470
The second thing that changes
culture is how you work.

00:21:08.470 --> 00:21:11.160
Now, I worked on a project that
most you know as Ecomagination.

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:14.510
It's the first $30 billion
spend on the green technology

00:21:14.510 --> 00:21:15.800
that General Electric did.

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:16.760
Well, one of the
things that people

00:21:16.760 --> 00:21:18.440
get wrong about
that is it was not

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:24.279
just to change the game about
power, which it was, partially.

00:21:24.279 --> 00:21:25.820
But it was also to
try and figure out

00:21:25.820 --> 00:21:28.160
how to get 28 divisions of
one of the world's largest

00:21:28.160 --> 00:21:30.170
companies to work in sync.

00:21:30.170 --> 00:21:33.260
So you either change
how people lead,

00:21:33.260 --> 00:21:35.150
or you change how they work.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:36.980
That's how culture gets changed.

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:39.750
But it takes a long time.

00:21:39.750 --> 00:21:42.177
So the issue is-- we all
know what's required.

00:21:42.177 --> 00:21:43.760
But are we willing
to put the time in?

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:46.900
So what's the answer?

00:21:46.900 --> 00:21:51.370
Well, one of my favorite answers
comes from an old philosophy

00:21:51.370 --> 00:21:52.710
called the Dao.

00:21:52.710 --> 00:21:56.350
And you're going to see
that a lot of my work

00:21:56.350 --> 00:21:59.180
and Staney's work really relates
from this old Chinese idea

00:21:59.180 --> 00:21:59.680
that's--

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:01.900
about 200 years before
Plato is around,

00:22:01.900 --> 00:22:03.370
people start writing about this.

00:22:03.370 --> 00:22:05.078
And at the heart of
the Dao is the notion

00:22:05.078 --> 00:22:08.140
of the yin and yang, the notion
that there are conflicting

00:22:08.140 --> 00:22:09.340
forces in the universe.

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:11.470
And these conflicting
forces produce hybrids.

00:22:11.470 --> 00:22:13.411
They create new ways
of doing things.

00:22:13.411 --> 00:22:15.910
Well, from this, the Chinese
have done something remarkable.

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:18.200
I've spent a lot of time
in China over the years.

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:21.989
The Chinese developed a way of
thinking called the "I Ching."

00:22:21.989 --> 00:22:24.280
And it's called-- sometimes
called the "Book of Ching."

00:22:24.280 --> 00:22:27.310
Just people use it for
predicting the future.

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:29.890
But it's really used so that
people can think through all

00:22:29.890 --> 00:22:31.270
the options that they've got.

00:22:31.270 --> 00:22:34.090
This is sometimes called
heuristics or cognitive

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:34.824
algorithms.

00:22:34.824 --> 00:22:36.990
Finally, out of this, there's
a lot of how-to books.

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:39.340
And the most famous one is a
book called "The Art of War,"

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:40.060
written by Sun Tzu.

00:22:40.060 --> 00:22:42.280
Whether that's a real person
or not's a real controversy,

00:22:42.280 --> 00:22:42.779
right?

00:22:42.779 --> 00:22:44.710
And then finally, the
family household--

00:22:44.710 --> 00:22:46.840
how to use this day
in and day out-- well,

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:48.790
feng shui, the whole
notion of a luopan,

00:22:48.790 --> 00:22:51.206
the whole notion of having a
compass to put this together.

00:22:51.206 --> 00:22:53.980
What it means is you don't
have to have inputs and outputs

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:57.460
and process because you're
thinking the way I'm thinking.

00:22:57.460 --> 00:22:59.080
And you're looking
at all the options.

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:02.514
So I don't have to supervise
you and tell you what to do.

00:23:02.514 --> 00:23:04.180
Well, this is the
heart of our thinking.

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:05.596
And this is the
heart of our book.

00:23:05.596 --> 00:23:08.480
We had this sort of
revelation in the early 1990s,

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:10.596
and that was the most
innovative companies,

00:23:10.596 --> 00:23:12.220
when we start looking
at predictability

00:23:12.220 --> 00:23:14.219
of what was going to make
an innovative company,

00:23:14.219 --> 00:23:17.090
were companies that had
constructive conflict.

00:23:17.090 --> 00:23:18.622
Now, this is
important because when

00:23:18.622 --> 00:23:20.080
I talk about
constructive conflict,

00:23:20.080 --> 00:23:22.490
I'm not talking about talking
disrespectfully to people.

00:23:22.490 --> 00:23:24.460
That's not what I mean.

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:26.440
I don't mean
marginalizing people.

00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:30.850
I mean we have fine regard,
filial piety, collegial piety

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:31.510
for each other.

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:33.176
Hopefully, we have--
we like each other,

00:23:33.176 --> 00:23:34.550
maybe love each other.

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:38.060
But it means when it
comes to ideas, we engage.

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:40.570
Now, engagement usually
means-- we talk about

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:43.160
engagement-- oh, you really
like being here at work.

00:23:43.160 --> 00:23:43.690
No.

00:23:43.690 --> 00:23:45.190
When we start looking
at innovation,

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:46.460
it means you have an idea.

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:47.380
And I have an idea.

00:23:47.380 --> 00:23:48.757
And they're different ideas.

00:23:48.757 --> 00:23:51.340
Instead of being on social media
and us sniping at each other,

00:23:51.340 --> 00:23:54.040
us trolling each other,
I'm going to engage you.

00:23:54.040 --> 00:23:56.060
I'm going to get nose
to nose to you and say,

00:23:56.060 --> 00:23:57.374
I think it should be like this.

00:23:57.374 --> 00:23:59.790
And you're going to say, I
think it needs to be like this.

00:23:59.790 --> 00:24:02.200
Now, this is a caution
to millennials.

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:06.100
This is not an opportunity
for compromise.

00:24:06.100 --> 00:24:10.360
This is trying to push this to
the new place, the next idea,

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:12.670
the third way, a new way.

00:24:12.670 --> 00:24:15.490
This becomes the generative
power of innovation,

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:16.780
where you do it all.

00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:17.380
Think about it for a minute.

00:24:17.380 --> 00:24:18.610
Think about the
health care debate.

00:24:18.610 --> 00:24:20.920
I got to give my TED Talk
when President Obama rolled

00:24:20.920 --> 00:24:23.170
out the Affordable Health
Care Act at the White House.

00:24:23.170 --> 00:24:23.729
It was great.

00:24:23.729 --> 00:24:25.270
The problem is you
got one group that

00:24:25.270 --> 00:24:26.240
says this should all be public.

00:24:26.240 --> 00:24:28.323
And the other group says
it should all be private.

00:24:28.323 --> 00:24:30.130
Are those really our options?

00:24:30.130 --> 00:24:32.770
Aren't the options
everything in between and how

00:24:32.770 --> 00:24:34.409
do we take that forward, right?

00:24:34.409 --> 00:24:35.950
We spent a trillion
dollars basically

00:24:35.950 --> 00:24:37.866
yelling at each other,
yelling over the fence.

00:24:37.866 --> 00:24:41.390
So my point about social media
is we haven't had conflict.

00:24:41.390 --> 00:24:42.740
We've had yelling at each other.

00:24:42.740 --> 00:24:44.144
But no one is engaged.

00:24:44.144 --> 00:24:45.310
Is everybody following this?

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:47.950
So the thing is we're
going to engage ideas.

00:24:47.950 --> 00:24:51.590
So there is no such
thing as a safe place.

00:24:51.590 --> 00:24:52.990
It means if we
talk respectfully,

00:24:52.990 --> 00:24:53.950
we're going to engage.

00:24:53.950 --> 00:24:55.658
And this means at the
heart of innovation

00:24:55.658 --> 00:24:57.070
is this concept of diversity.

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:59.032
So diversity is more
than just a moral issue.

00:24:59.032 --> 00:25:00.490
And of course, it
is a moral issue.

00:25:00.490 --> 00:25:01.390
But it's more.

00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:03.400
And it's not just the
color of your skin.

00:25:03.400 --> 00:25:05.240
It's your belief system.

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:06.684
It's your cognitive maps.

00:25:06.684 --> 00:25:07.600
It's how you interact.

00:25:07.600 --> 00:25:08.870
It's your profession.

00:25:08.870 --> 00:25:12.880
So to do this, Staney
and I built our model

00:25:12.880 --> 00:25:14.140
on Quinn and Cameron's model.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:15.940
Bob Quinn had been
here, I believe.

00:25:15.940 --> 00:25:17.500
And he was sort of
one of my mentors,

00:25:17.500 --> 00:25:20.320
along with CK Prahalad
and Rudolf Arnheim.

00:25:20.320 --> 00:25:22.750
Quinn-- this is their model
called the Competing Values

00:25:22.750 --> 00:25:23.474
Framework.

00:25:23.474 --> 00:25:25.265
We took it towards the
innovation direction

00:25:25.265 --> 00:25:27.820
and did a lot of research on
it over the past 30 years.

00:25:27.820 --> 00:25:29.710
And it's often referred
to as the innovation

00:25:29.710 --> 00:25:31.900
genome-- if you read the popular
literature, the innovation

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:32.210
code.

00:25:32.210 --> 00:25:33.640
So we're the developers of that.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:36.730
And it basically says there
are four types of innovators.

00:25:36.730 --> 00:25:38.800
And they compete
against each other.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:41.110
And the key to
innovation is following

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:44.730
these kitty-corner competitions
and looking for hybrids.

00:25:44.730 --> 00:25:46.480
So I'm going to explain
what each of these

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:47.780
means in just a minute.

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:54.370
But to put it simply, innovation
has longitude and latitude.

00:25:54.370 --> 00:25:57.212
There are two continuums in
which you have to look at.

00:25:57.212 --> 00:25:59.170
And if you can figure
out those two continuums,

00:25:59.170 --> 00:26:02.810
the most important thing are the
dynamics between the opposites.

00:26:02.810 --> 00:26:05.440
Now, I want to emphasize this
is not an opposite of type.

00:26:05.440 --> 00:26:07.310
This is not an
opposite of style.

00:26:07.310 --> 00:26:09.370
This is what you're
trying to create destroys

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:10.690
what I'm trying to create.

00:26:10.690 --> 00:26:14.170
So when quality goes
up, you reduce errors

00:26:14.170 --> 00:26:16.330
and innovation goes down.

00:26:16.330 --> 00:26:18.820
When innovation goes
up, I introduce errors.

00:26:18.820 --> 00:26:21.880
This is sometimes called
economy at risk, right?

00:26:21.880 --> 00:26:23.170
So there's a trade-off.

00:26:23.170 --> 00:26:26.620
What we're saying is when these
two things show up together,

00:26:26.620 --> 00:26:28.270
what we've learned
in our research

00:26:28.270 --> 00:26:31.330
is those stocks
over time outperform

00:26:31.330 --> 00:26:33.190
all the other stocks, right?

00:26:33.190 --> 00:26:35.912
And they outperform the
indexes that people have.

00:26:35.912 --> 00:26:37.870
So these conflicts are
going to become central.

00:26:37.870 --> 00:26:39.703
So let me talk a little
bit about conflicts.

00:26:39.703 --> 00:26:41.680
Now, first of all, this
is not just about you.

00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:43.304
I like to call these
Russian matryoshka

00:26:43.304 --> 00:26:44.940
dolls, or Russian
nesting dolls, right?

00:26:44.940 --> 00:26:45.160
I don't know.

00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:45.960
Do you do this?

00:26:45.960 --> 00:26:47.070
I read self-help books.

00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:48.330
And then I go, you know
what I'm going to do?

00:26:48.330 --> 00:26:49.320
I'm going to do this.

00:26:49.320 --> 00:26:50.820
I'm going to go
to Traverse City.

00:26:50.820 --> 00:26:52.710
And I'm just going
to quit my job.

00:26:52.710 --> 00:26:55.620
And I'm going to write
a crappy science fiction

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:56.740
novel-- is what I'm doing.

00:26:56.740 --> 00:26:58.948
And I've worked hard in my
life, made a little money.

00:26:58.948 --> 00:26:59.700
I'm doing OK.

00:26:59.700 --> 00:27:00.554
I'm chucking it all.

00:27:00.554 --> 00:27:01.470
That's what I'm doing.

00:27:01.470 --> 00:27:02.553
Anybody get to that point?

00:27:02.553 --> 00:27:05.100
I've had enough of this.

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:05.760
Yeah.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:08.480
But there's another nesting
doll in my nesting doll.

00:27:08.480 --> 00:27:10.080
It's called, I'm married.

00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:11.290
And I have three children.

00:27:11.290 --> 00:27:12.172
And I have a dean.

00:27:12.172 --> 00:27:13.380
And I have business partners.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:15.430
And I have people who
count on me, right?

00:27:15.430 --> 00:27:15.930
Yeah.

00:27:15.930 --> 00:27:16.680
That's the other part.

00:27:16.680 --> 00:27:19.138
And then what happens after
that is there's the real world.

00:27:19.138 --> 00:27:20.440
That's the big nesting doll.

00:27:20.440 --> 00:27:21.780
There's a pandemic.

00:27:21.780 --> 00:27:22.576
There's a war.

00:27:22.576 --> 00:27:23.700
There's a financial crisis.

00:27:23.700 --> 00:27:25.470
Boy, you young people
got blown out bad.

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:25.970
No, wait.

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:27.630
That was pretty bad.

00:27:27.630 --> 00:27:28.320
Yeah.

00:27:28.320 --> 00:27:31.590
The notion is you don't
act alone, do you?

00:27:31.590 --> 00:27:34.830
You act in accordance
to your community.

00:27:34.830 --> 00:27:37.620
And you act in accordance
to the situation.

00:27:37.620 --> 00:27:39.714
So it's not about you.

00:27:39.714 --> 00:27:41.880
It's not about, I'm this
type, and that's all equal.

00:27:41.880 --> 00:27:43.780
That's not what's going on.

00:27:43.780 --> 00:27:46.230
What's going on is there's
situational effectiveness.

00:27:46.230 --> 00:27:48.600
And it's not situation
like, this is awkward,

