What's it really mean?

00:33:30.500 --> 00:33:32.851
It's 20% done on a good day.

00:33:32.851 --> 00:33:34.850
You're not any-- and the
artist will take credit

00:33:34.850 --> 00:33:36.433
for everything, don't
they, engineers?

00:33:36.433 --> 00:33:37.220
They take credit.

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:37.490
Yeah.

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:38.781
That's the way the artists are.

00:33:38.781 --> 00:33:40.451
They crow about it.

00:33:40.451 --> 00:33:42.950
So what you can do, artists,
when dealing with an engineer--

00:33:42.950 --> 00:33:45.380
one, show up on time.

00:33:45.380 --> 00:33:47.079
You think they don't notice.

00:33:47.079 --> 00:33:49.370
Oh, the engineers are the
most passive-aggressive group

00:33:49.370 --> 00:33:50.036
you've got here.

00:33:50.036 --> 00:33:52.460
And on a dark night on a
dark road, you'll disappear.

00:33:52.460 --> 00:33:55.110
They got a file on you like
J. Edgar Hoover, right?

00:33:55.110 --> 00:33:57.070
They absolutely
watch you, right?

00:33:57.070 --> 00:33:57.570
No.

00:33:57.570 --> 00:33:57.800
Look it.

00:33:57.800 --> 00:33:59.030
Yeah, you know this, right?

00:33:59.030 --> 00:34:00.650
The notion is look at the data.

00:34:00.650 --> 00:34:02.840
Actually read the data, right?

00:34:02.840 --> 00:34:04.130
How about that for a change?

00:34:04.130 --> 00:34:05.887
And follow the accepted form.

00:34:05.887 --> 00:34:07.970
And in the book, there's
a lot of keys about this.

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:10.190
Now, here's the point.

00:34:10.190 --> 00:34:13.550
The point is the
success of this group

00:34:13.550 --> 00:34:16.723
