00:45:04.370 --> 00:45:05.786
we avoid, the uncle
we suck up to?

00:45:05.786 --> 00:45:07.110
Who are you in the family?

00:45:07.110 --> 00:45:09.097
The notion is you're
always going to see this.

00:45:09.097 --> 00:45:10.680
And what happens is
we have a tendency

00:45:10.680 --> 00:45:14.430
to vilify the people who
aren't like us instead

00:45:14.430 --> 00:45:15.832
of understanding them.

00:45:15.832 --> 00:45:17.290
And that becomes
the big challenge.

00:45:17.290 --> 00:45:19.498
So we have to have the right
person at the right job.

00:45:19.498 --> 00:45:22.050
Now, I'm going to throw some
self-help stuff out the window.

00:45:22.050 --> 00:45:23.051
It's going to upset you.

00:45:23.051 --> 00:45:25.508
But I'm going to tell you what
basically the research says.

00:45:25.508 --> 00:45:27.930
First, the assumption of
type doesn't mean competency.

00:45:27.930 --> 00:45:28.717
Oh, I'm an artist.

00:45:28.717 --> 00:45:29.550
But you suck, right?

00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:31.080
You're just not a good artist.

00:45:31.080 --> 00:45:33.163
The assumption that talent
can be developed-- this

00:45:33.163 --> 00:45:34.280
is my favorite one.

00:45:34.280 --> 00:45:36.050
It can be developed to a point.

00:45:36.050 --> 00:45:38.460
But you're not going to make
Mozart or Michael Jordan.

00:45:38.460 --> 00:45:41.170
Those are things that are a
confluence of natural talent

00:45:41.170 --> 00:45:43.280
and the situation that
they find themself in.

00:45:43.280 --> 00:45:45.080
Assumption that all types
are equal-- they're not.

00:45:45.080 --> 00:45:47.246
If I'm an investment banker,
what am I trying to do?

00:45:47.246 --> 00:45:48.470
I'm trying to do blue stuff.

00:45:48.470 --> 00:45:50.840
If I'm a university professor,
I'm trying to do yellow stuff.

00:45:50.840 --> 00:45:52.850
So the blues are going to be
more valuable in one situation,

00:45:52.850 --> 00:45:53.824
the yellows in another.

00:45:53.824 --> 00:45:55.490
And finally, the
assumption that balance

00:45:55.490 --> 00:45:57.045
is better-- not necessarily so.

00:45:57.045 --> 00:45:58.670
When I'm starting a
project, the greens

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:01.490
are geniuses because they love
the ambiguity-- make stuff

00:46:01.490 --> 00:46:02.354
as they go along.

00:46:02.354 --> 00:46:03.770
At the end, the
reds are geniuses.

00:46:03.770 --> 00:46:05.710
And everybody in
between is a genius.

00:46:05.710 --> 00:46:07.730
Now, remember, I haven't
spoken about the Xers.

00:46:07.730 --> 00:46:10.640
Xers-- what they're
genius is at is connecting

00:46:10.640 --> 00:46:11.980
boomers and millennials.

00:46:11.980 --> 00:46:13.400
Xers are the
smallest generation.

00:46:13.400 --> 00:46:15.320
But they're the most
ambidextrous generation

00:46:15.320 --> 00:46:16.130
we've seen.

00:46:16.130 --> 00:46:18.440
So the only reason I talk
about boomers and millennials

00:46:18.440 --> 00:46:20.810
is we're the largest
generations by far, relatively.

00:46:20.810 --> 00:46:21.870
X are smaller.

00:46:21.870 --> 00:46:23.120
Gen Z are going to be smaller.

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:25.040
But they might be the
most valuable, right?

00:46:25.040 --> 00:46:27.140
And incidentally,
millennials, remember this--

00:46:27.140 --> 00:46:29.199
there's more of you now
than there are of us.

00:46:29.199 --> 00:46:30.740
You're on the sunny
side of the hill.

00:46:30.740 --> 00:46:32.573
And if you ever figure
that out politically,

00:46:32.573 --> 00:46:35.510
boy, it's going to get real
interesting real fast, right?

00:46:35.510 --> 00:46:37.100
So the direction you
move under stress

00:46:37.100 --> 00:46:38.150
is what people really are.

00:46:38.150 --> 00:46:40.100
So if you really want to
know what somebody is,

00:46:40.100 --> 00:46:42.183
see what they do when
they're really under stress.

00:46:42.183 --> 00:46:44.480
Do they go get on social
media, talk to their friends?

00:46:44.480 --> 00:46:45.950
Do they shorten the
field and sort of look

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:47.158
at the three things in front?

00:46:47.158 --> 00:46:48.320
Do they look at the data?

00:46:48.320 --> 00:46:50.395
Do they go weasel out of
stuff and sort of go off

00:46:50.395 --> 00:46:52.520
the reservation and do all
kinds of creative stuff?

00:46:52.520 --> 00:46:54.410
That will tell you
what that person is.

00:46:54.410 --> 00:46:57.275
But here becomes the
money part of this.

00:46:57.275 --> 00:46:58.670
This is the key part.

00:46:58.670 --> 00:47:00.327
How you innovate is
what you innovate.

00:47:00.327 --> 00:47:01.910
How you innovate is
what you innovate.

00:47:01.910 --> 00:47:03.076
You want radical innovation?

00:47:03.076 --> 00:47:04.370
You got to embrace the artist.

00:47:04.370 --> 00:47:05.090
You want to get scale?

00:47:05.090 --> 00:47:06.527
You got to embrace the engineer.

00:47:06.527 --> 00:47:07.360
You want to go fast?

00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:08.540
You got to embrace the athlete.

00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:09.590
You want to build
something sustainable?

00:47:09.590 --> 00:47:10.850
Embrace the sage.

00:47:10.850 --> 00:47:12.867
And you need all
four of these to win.

00:47:12.867 --> 00:47:15.200
So here's the biggest problems
you're going to run into.

00:47:15.200 --> 00:47:17.840
And we're going to talk about
the data in one second on this.

00:47:17.840 --> 00:47:20.210
The biggest problem you
have is that the people

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:22.820
who are in the green
position are orphans.

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:24.065
The artists are orphans.

00:47:24.065 --> 00:47:25.940
The city that you're in
right now, Ann Arbor,

00:47:25.940 --> 00:47:27.740
has more venture
capital per person

00:47:27.740 --> 00:47:29.240
than any city in
the United States.

00:47:29.240 --> 00:47:32.570
The problem is, does it relate
to anything else in this state?

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:33.250
No.

00:47:33.250 --> 00:47:34.350
You're orphans.

00:47:34.350 --> 00:47:36.830
So the problem is
you got to snuggle up

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:39.260
to people who are
trying to make a living

00:47:39.260 --> 00:47:41.130
and do things in other areas.

00:47:41.130 --> 00:47:43.400
The second problem are
the blues and the yellows.

00:47:43.400 --> 00:47:45.980
And the problem is they're
oppositional, dogs and cats.

00:47:45.980 --> 00:47:48.590
So one, you have to really
engage the conflict.

00:47:48.590 --> 00:47:50.847
And the second problem is
this is by far the longest

00:47:50.847 --> 00:47:51.680
cycle of innovation.

00:47:51.680 --> 00:47:53.096
It's sometimes
called Death Valley

00:47:53.096 --> 00:47:54.440
or the bottom of the bathtub.

00:47:54.440 --> 00:47:56.610
How many have been in a
project that lost momentum?

00:47:56.610 --> 00:47:58.485
Anybody been on a project
that lost momentum,

00:47:58.485 --> 00:47:59.210
and you sort of--

00:47:59.210 --> 00:48:01.070
and you have to platoon
players in and out?

00:48:01.070 --> 00:48:01.570
Yeah.

00:48:01.570 --> 00:48:02.430
This is that part.

00:48:02.430 --> 00:48:04.820
And finally, the reds, the
engineers-- the problem

00:48:04.820 --> 00:48:06.950
is they're so
optimized that there's

00:48:06.950 --> 00:48:09.570
no room to try anything else.

00:48:09.570 --> 00:48:11.156
And so when the
new thing shows up,

00:48:11.156 --> 00:48:12.780
they're not prepared
for the new things

00:48:12.780 --> 00:48:15.920
because every moment of their
life is basically taken up.

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:17.657
So we have to rely
on each other.

00:48:17.657 --> 00:48:20.240
Now, the other thing that's very
important about the dynamics,

00:48:20.240 --> 00:48:22.215
which is a key
point, is innovation

00:48:22.215 --> 00:48:24.590
doesn't move from the inside
out-- moves from the outside

00:48:24.590 --> 00:48:25.160
in.

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:26.380
And think about
this for a minute.

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:27.560
When do people really change?

00:48:27.560 --> 00:48:28.684
When do you really change--

00:48:28.684 --> 00:48:30.300
I mean, really?

00:48:30.300 --> 00:48:30.800
Yeah.

00:48:30.800 --> 00:48:32.900
When you made a mistake,
when your life sucks,

00:48:32.900 --> 00:48:35.030
when you get divorced,
when you lose a job,

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:36.809
when your house
goes away, somebody

00:48:36.809 --> 00:48:37.850
close to you passes away.

00:48:37.850 --> 00:48:40.250
Why do you change
when your life sucks?

00:48:40.250 --> 00:48:41.810
Because the risk
of trying something

00:48:41.810 --> 00:48:44.810
radical and the reward
of seeing where you're at

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:47.154
is reversed in a crisis.

00:48:47.154 --> 00:48:48.320
Is everybody following this?

00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:51.710
Whether this is Apple
trading at $3 a share

00:48:51.710 --> 00:48:55.910
in 1997, whether this is
Gandhi in the march to the sea,

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:57.260
it also has a negative effect.

00:48:57.260 --> 00:48:59.450
This is also Hitler
and the Brownshirts.

00:48:59.450 --> 00:49:01.580
The notion is it
doesn't move inside out.

00:49:01.580 --> 00:49:04.576
It moves outside in, where
the middle of the organization

00:49:04.576 --> 00:49:05.450
is trying to do what?

00:49:05.450 --> 00:49:06.190
Maintain.

00:49:06.190 --> 00:49:07.690
And the outside's
trying to do what?

00:49:07.690 --> 00:49:09.072
Introduce diversity.

00:49:09.072 --> 00:49:11.030
Now, the other time that
people change is when?

00:49:11.030 --> 00:49:12.320
When they're on a roll.

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:13.220
You win the lottery.

00:49:13.220 --> 00:49:13.970
You got promoted.

00:49:13.970 --> 00:49:15.737
You're in love, all that stuff.

00:49:15.737 --> 00:49:16.820
Why do you try stuff then?

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:17.891
Because the same thing--

00:49:17.891 --> 00:49:19.390
the risk of trying
something radical

00:49:19.390 --> 00:49:21.598
and the reward of where
you're at is reversed, right?

00:49:21.598 --> 00:49:23.270
It's called risk
capital in our world.

00:49:23.270 --> 00:49:24.350
And incidentally,
Google, you've had

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.224
a lot of risk capital
over the past 10 years,

00:49:26.224 --> 00:49:27.350
a lot of risk capital.

00:49:27.350 --> 00:49:30.020
So the notion is don't launch
innovation from the inside out.

00:49:30.020 --> 00:49:31.730
Because what'll happen to
that innovation is what?

00:49:31.730 --> 00:49:33.580
The organization will
begin to converge it.

00:49:33.580 --> 00:49:35.930
It will begin to make
it more incremental.

00:49:35.930 --> 00:49:37.670
You have to start
at the perimeter.

00:49:37.670 --> 00:49:40.460
The farther away you can
be from headquarters,

00:49:40.460 --> 00:49:43.160
the farther you can be
away from the watchful eye,

00:49:43.160 --> 00:49:44.630
the better off
you're going to be.

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:47.220
Now, this leads us to
this last slide here.

00:49:47.220 --> 00:49:51.630
This is referred to as
the Schumpeter cycle.

00:49:51.630 --> 00:49:53.060
And the Schumpeter cycle--

00:49:53.060 --> 00:49:55.250
I want you to think
about this for a minute.

00:49:55.250 --> 00:49:59.360
First of all, organizations are
created by greens, typically.

00:49:59.360 --> 00:50:02.140
They want to have freedom.

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:03.740
This is Larry and Sergey--

00:50:03.740 --> 00:50:05.700
created in a garage
in Menlo, right?

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:06.860
This is what this was.

00:50:06.860 --> 00:50:08.690
But next, we got to
get money involved.

00:50:08.690 --> 00:50:11.500
And these are the people who
gave you money early on, right?

00:50:11.500 --> 00:50:13.745
These are the big
Apollo funds and things

00:50:13.745 --> 00:50:15.620
that gave Google money
at the very beginning.

00:50:15.620 --> 00:50:17.057
And they focus the two.

00:50:17.057 --> 00:50:18.890
Then what happens is
you grow ballistically.

00:50:18.890 --> 00:50:20.090
We got to get the
yellows on board

00:50:20.090 --> 00:50:20.990
because we got to
have the right people,

00:50:20.990 --> 00:50:22.650
sell to the right people,
build the right community.

00:50:22.650 --> 00:50:24.941
And then we have to have,
ultimately, the reds on board

00:50:24.941 --> 00:50:26.484
because we have to get to scale.

00:50:26.484 --> 00:50:27.650
Is everybody following this?

00:50:27.650 --> 00:50:29.480
Now, what's
important about this?

00:50:29.480 --> 00:50:31.880
Once we get to
scale, the problem

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:34.970
is every capital committee
person, every metric

00:50:34.970 --> 00:50:39.140
that we've got, every
process that we've run,

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:43.330
is designed to do
what to deviance?

00:50:43.330 --> 00:50:45.850
To eliminate it.

00:50:45.850 --> 00:50:48.370
Why didn't Sears become Amazon?

00:50:48.370 --> 00:50:51.820
Why didn't Microsoft
become Google, right?

00:50:51.820 --> 00:50:55.150
Why didn't McDonald's
become Starbucks?

00:50:55.150 --> 00:50:57.130
It had nothing to
do with competition.

00:50:57.130 --> 00:50:59.140
They had all the stuff
in the lab, right?

00:50:59.140 --> 00:51:00.090
You know this.

00:51:00.090 --> 00:51:02.410
The notion is, and this
is the radical part

00:51:02.410 --> 00:51:05.492
of this whole discussion-- what
Schumpeter said is radical.

00:51:05.492 --> 00:51:07.450
And whether-- it depends
on who you're talking.

00:51:07.450 --> 00:51:09.770
We had six or seven Nobel
Prize winners in economics

00:51:09.770 --> 00:51:10.630
since 1969.

00:51:10.630 --> 00:51:11.680
I've talked about this.

00:51:11.680 --> 00:51:15.040
The radical part of this is
that what Schumpeter said

00:51:15.040 --> 00:51:17.460
is that we're not
destroyed by competitors.

00:51:17.460 --> 00:51:20.939
What Schumpeter said
is we kill ourselves.

00:51:20.939 --> 00:51:22.480
We have seen the
enemy, and he is us.

00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:24.850
Our dominant logic
becomes so strong,

00:51:24.850 --> 00:51:26.680
we can't get over it, right?

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:28.150
And as a nation
state in America,

00:51:28.150 --> 00:51:30.130
aren't we suffering
from this right now,

00:51:30.130 --> 00:51:32.680
that we can't get over
our dominant logic?

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:34.360
We can't see the other.

00:51:34.360 --> 00:51:38.050
He calls this the point
of creative destruction.

00:51:38.050 --> 00:51:41.560
And ironically, organizations
that begin to fail quickly

00:51:41.560 --> 00:51:43.240
have a much better
chance of innovating

00:51:43.240 --> 00:51:45.730
because they have to go back
to the beginning of the cycle.

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:47.474
Apple trading at $3 a share--

00:51:47.474 --> 00:51:48.640
is everybody following this?

00:51:48.640 --> 00:51:50.680
But think about General
Motors in 1950--

00:51:50.680 --> 00:51:53.280
had 53% of the
world car market--

00:51:53.280 --> 00:51:55.491
drip, drip, drip.

00:51:55.491 --> 00:51:56.490
It's called flat-lining.

00:51:56.490 --> 00:51:59.130
So the notion is there's an
interesting sort of confounding

00:51:59.130 --> 00:52:02.610
part to this, where even
though there's tension,

00:52:02.610 --> 00:52:06.150
the best thing that can happen
is when one cycle shifts

00:52:06.150 --> 00:52:08.854
into the other cycle in a
relatively straightforward way

00:52:08.854 --> 00:52:10.520
so we can put cause
and effect together.

00:52:10.520 --> 00:52:12.515
So here's what--
here's the thing to do.

00:52:12.515 --> 00:52:13.800
Then I'm going to turn
this over to Staney.

00:52:13.800 --> 00:52:15.216
She's going to
talk about the book

00:52:15.216 --> 00:52:16.980
and what you can do
here in your work.

00:52:16.980 --> 00:52:19.000
Stop believing you
can see the future.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:21.850
Make smaller, wider bets,
choosing big over fast.

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:22.350
No.

00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:23.340
Pick up your pace.

00:52:23.340 --> 00:52:25.290
Go faster, right?

00:52:25.290 --> 00:52:27.600
Mistaking your managers
for innovators-- no.

00:52:27.600 --> 00:52:31.830
Encourage, encourage,
and support your weirdos.

00:52:31.830 --> 00:52:33.257
We need weirdos.

00:52:33.257 --> 00:52:35.340
And incidentally, if you're
an organization that's

00:52:35.340 --> 00:52:37.714
really green, weirdos are reds.

00:52:37.714 --> 00:52:38.880
Is everybody following this?

00:52:38.880 --> 00:52:41.310
If you're-- if you're
a yellow organization,

00:52:41.310 --> 00:52:42.540
the weirdos are blue.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:43.860
They're just not like you.

00:52:43.860 --> 00:52:46.980
Having more ambition
than capability--

00:52:46.980 --> 00:52:48.390
talent matters.

00:52:48.390 --> 00:52:50.765
You got to go out and build
on the capability you have.

00:52:50.765 --> 00:52:52.140
I love what the
armed forces say.

00:52:52.140 --> 00:52:53.490
You don't fight with
the army you want.

00:52:53.490 --> 00:52:55.926
You fight with the army you
have, which I think is great.

00:52:55.926 --> 00:52:57.300
Starting at the
center, move out.

00:52:57.300 --> 00:52:58.500
It's not student body.

00:52:58.500 --> 00:52:59.622
It's a perimeter game.

00:52:59.622 --> 00:53:01.080
I worked on a
project that you know

00:53:01.080 --> 00:53:03.359
that was originally called C2.

00:53:03.359 --> 00:53:04.400
You know it as Coke Zero.

00:53:04.400 --> 00:53:05.984
I worked on Coke Zero.

00:53:05.984 --> 00:53:07.650
The problem with Coke
Zero was everybody

00:53:07.650 --> 00:53:09.900
thought they had it right,
and they launched it as C2.

00:53:09.900 --> 00:53:12.900
We had to move it out of sight,
work it out off Broadway,

00:53:12.900 --> 00:53:13.650
and bring it back.

00:53:13.650 --> 00:53:15.870
And that became Coke Zero.

00:53:15.870 --> 00:53:17.256
Listening to the wrong people--

00:53:17.256 --> 00:53:18.630
don't listen to
the customers who

00:53:18.630 --> 00:53:20.780
are your big customers, because
are they going to move first?

00:53:20.780 --> 00:53:21.720
They're going to move last.

00:53:21.720 --> 00:53:23.270
Finally, failing to
connect the dots-- you

00:53:23.270 --> 00:53:24.120
got to connect the dots.

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:25.110
That's why we're here.

00:53:25.110 --> 00:53:27.220
You got to put all
four of these together.

00:53:27.220 --> 00:53:28.500
Now, the last part of this--

00:53:28.500 --> 00:53:30.450
I want Staney to come
