00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:57.160
that you have to exercise.

00:53:57.160 --> 00:53:59.062
Once you got it, it
becomes really easy.

00:53:59.062 --> 00:54:00.520
But if you've never
done it before,

00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:01.936
it could be pretty
awkward and can

00:54:01.936 --> 00:54:06.130
be quite difficult, and
actually quite intimidating,

00:54:06.130 --> 00:54:06.770
to start first.

00:54:06.770 --> 00:54:09.310
So the first thing
that you have to do

00:54:09.310 --> 00:54:11.320
is really assemble a
diversity of perspective.

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:14.040
What I love about this building
when Scott gave us a tour

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:17.560
is there's so many spaces
here that are very open spaces

00:54:17.560 --> 00:54:19.330
that anybody can just go to.

00:54:19.330 --> 00:54:23.560
So that's the first thing-- is
I always talk to our clients.

00:54:23.560 --> 00:54:26.440
And I will say, there has to be
a space where people actually

00:54:26.440 --> 00:54:28.570
can just go in and
just talk to one

00:54:28.570 --> 00:54:30.490
another like a
normal human being.

00:54:30.490 --> 00:54:31.990
If you put them
just in cubicles,

00:54:31.990 --> 00:54:33.820
and there's no way for
them to go anywhere,

00:54:33.820 --> 00:54:36.220
how are they actually
going to meet other people?

00:54:36.220 --> 00:54:38.995
But this also talks
about recruiting.

00:54:38.995 --> 00:54:42.130
In a company, you can't just
recruit one type of person

00:54:42.130 --> 00:54:43.630
or one type of skill.

00:54:43.630 --> 00:54:46.720
You might want to combine the
skills you're looking for,

00:54:46.720 --> 00:54:48.820
with the kind of age
you're looking for,

00:54:48.820 --> 00:54:50.550
with the kind of
skin color you're

00:54:50.550 --> 00:54:52.630
looking for, with the
kind of background,

00:54:52.630 --> 00:54:54.760
with the kind of
diversity of thought.

00:54:54.760 --> 00:54:56.660
Where is this
person coming from?

00:54:56.660 --> 00:55:00.190
So you have to have a pool
of people in which you can

00:55:00.190 --> 00:55:02.390
communicate on a regular basis.

00:55:02.390 --> 00:55:06.850
And I think this is what
Jeff always talks about is--

00:55:06.850 --> 00:55:08.050
we have three children.

00:55:08.050 --> 00:55:09.620
And my youngest is 16.

00:55:09.620 --> 00:55:11.440
And they're always
on social media.

00:55:11.440 --> 00:55:13.180
And what I do see
in social media,

00:55:13.180 --> 00:55:16.900
too, is people
start only looking--

00:55:16.900 --> 00:55:18.880
my friends are my friends.

00:55:18.880 --> 00:55:21.880
And my friends have the
similar view that I do.

00:55:21.880 --> 00:55:25.240
And I get frustrated when I see
a different point of view that,

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:27.410
to me, was attacking
my point of view.

00:55:27.410 --> 00:55:28.597
I don't like that.

00:55:28.597 --> 00:55:29.680
And I know people do that.

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:31.570
We have our own niches.

00:55:31.570 --> 00:55:33.640
And that's actually
quite dangerous for what

00:55:33.640 --> 00:55:35.150
we want to do.

00:55:35.150 --> 00:55:37.210
We should just open
up and start talking,

00:55:37.210 --> 00:55:39.070
have a conversation
with somebody else who's

00:55:39.070 --> 00:55:41.200
very different from us.

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:43.810
I was just talking to my intern.

00:55:43.810 --> 00:55:46.230
And she was talking about,
how do you meet new people?

00:55:46.230 --> 00:55:48.132
And I said, well, I used
just to go to cafés.

00:55:48.132 --> 00:55:49.590
There are a lot of
people in cafés.

00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:52.716
She's like, I've never met
any new person in a café.

00:55:52.716 --> 00:55:54.590
I'm like, it's a totally
different world now.

00:55:54.590 --> 00:55:56.030
I totally get that.

00:55:56.030 --> 00:55:57.520
But I think that's
why you actually

00:55:57.520 --> 00:55:59.990
have to make the first step.

00:55:59.990 --> 00:56:04.220
And so this is the kind of
types of the four colors

00:56:04.220 --> 00:56:04.970
that you can find.

00:56:04.970 --> 00:56:07.070
Usually, engineers
are-- they're organized.

00:56:07.070 --> 00:56:11.080
So they can be scientists,
analysts, those kind of things.

00:56:11.080 --> 00:56:12.910
And sages are
teachers and so forth.

00:56:12.910 --> 00:56:14.840
So you can look at that.

00:56:14.840 --> 00:56:18.010
But the second step is then
you have to actually engage it.

00:56:18.010 --> 00:56:21.250
So we're talking about if
we are doing brainstorming,

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:24.010
for example, to solve
a particular idea

00:56:24.010 --> 00:56:26.530
or a particular challenge
in your organization,

00:56:26.530 --> 00:56:29.870
gather everybody and make sure
there are all the four colors.

00:56:29.870 --> 00:56:32.050
And then put it in
one space, one room.

00:56:32.050 --> 00:56:33.307
And then just engage.

00:56:33.307 --> 00:56:34.390
You actually have to talk.

00:56:34.390 --> 00:56:36.700
This is what Jeff
was talking about.

00:56:36.700 --> 00:56:39.031
If you do not agree with
something, then say it.

00:56:39.031 --> 00:56:40.030
I don't agree with that.

00:56:40.030 --> 00:56:41.500
You don't have to be mean.

00:56:41.500 --> 00:56:42.792
You can be respectful.

00:56:42.792 --> 00:56:43.750
But you have to engage.

00:56:43.750 --> 00:56:46.970
And I think, and forgive
me if I'm wrong--

00:56:46.970 --> 00:56:50.140
but I also noticed that
in my children, especially

00:56:50.140 --> 00:56:54.260
the 16-year-old, he
doesn't like conflict.

00:56:54.260 --> 00:56:57.910
So he doesn't like telling
people, I don't agree with you.

00:56:57.910 --> 00:57:00.840
And it's easier for him
to do it in social media

00:57:00.840 --> 00:57:03.340
and to write something instead
of just walking to the person

00:57:03.340 --> 00:57:04.759
and say, I really disagree.

00:57:04.759 --> 00:57:06.800
And this is actually a
skill that you have to do.

00:57:06.800 --> 00:57:09.860
You actually have to engage
that with this open-mindedness

00:57:09.860 --> 00:57:11.300
and conversation.

00:57:11.300 --> 00:57:14.560
It's really when we create
a cognitive dissonance

00:57:14.560 --> 00:57:15.680
in our brain.

00:57:15.680 --> 00:57:18.110
And then we start
thinking about new things.

00:57:18.110 --> 00:57:22.330
So one of the things that we
also talk about is talk about--

00:57:22.330 --> 00:57:24.670
use this and say what worked
and what doesn't work.

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:26.740
And go through the
four colors to see

00:57:26.740 --> 00:57:29.020
what's working, what
doesn't right now,

00:57:29.020 --> 00:57:32.300
and to figure out what
solutions we can come up with.

00:57:32.300 --> 00:57:34.480
And when you get into
a really big conflict

00:57:34.480 --> 00:57:36.865
and you feel like you're
stuck, the third thing

00:57:36.865 --> 00:57:39.130
that you have to do
is really make sure

00:57:39.130 --> 00:57:41.050
that you establish that
shared goal or vision.

00:57:41.050 --> 00:57:42.700
Keep on reminding
everyone why are

00:57:42.700 --> 00:57:45.080
you there, why in this room.

00:57:45.080 --> 00:57:47.500
We are trying to solve
that particular problem.

00:57:47.500 --> 00:57:50.020
And just kind of stick with
it-- because if everybody has

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:52.820
the same goal, and everybody
agrees with that same goal,

00:57:52.820 --> 00:57:54.940
and they can remove their ego--

00:57:54.940 --> 00:57:56.270
I think that's a big thing--

00:57:56.270 --> 00:57:58.360
from the situation,
then we might

00:57:58.360 --> 00:58:00.910
be able to come
out with something.

00:58:00.910 --> 00:58:03.820
And the fourth one
is just then you

00:58:03.820 --> 00:58:06.220
have to construct
the hybrid solution.

00:58:06.220 --> 00:58:09.580
So brainstorm a lot of
arrays of good ideas

00:58:09.580 --> 00:58:12.250
and select the best ideas
from the four colors.

00:58:12.250 --> 00:58:15.760
And try to see, can I put the
green one with the red one?

00:58:15.760 --> 00:58:18.130
Could I put the blue
one and the yellow one?

00:58:18.130 --> 00:58:21.650
And we put some ideas and
some methods in the book.

00:58:21.650 --> 00:58:23.260
You can use metaphors.

00:58:23.260 --> 00:58:26.580
You could use different
kind of a creativity idea

00:58:26.580 --> 00:58:28.340
that we can put up together.

00:58:28.340 --> 00:58:31.790
And basically, the idea
is let's not compromise.

00:58:31.790 --> 00:58:33.610
Let's not choose
one idea to another.

00:58:33.610 --> 00:58:37.210
Let's figure out a way that
we can ascend all this,

00:58:37.210 --> 00:58:40.170
get all disagreement together,
listen to one another,

00:58:40.170 --> 00:58:44.050
create a bond and learn how
to communicate with another,

00:58:44.050 --> 00:58:46.863
and then come out with
a better solution.

00:58:46.863 --> 00:58:48.160
Jeff?

00:58:48.160 --> 00:58:51.830
JEFF DEGRAFF: Well, thank you.

00:58:51.830 --> 00:58:53.040
Let's finish up here.

00:58:53.040 --> 00:58:54.110
So what's the point?

00:58:54.110 --> 00:58:55.827
Take a higher point
of view, right?

00:58:55.827 --> 00:58:56.660
It's hard, isn't it?

00:58:56.660 --> 00:58:58.700
It's hard with all of the--

00:58:58.700 --> 00:58:59.390
all the anger.

00:58:59.390 --> 00:59:01.181
It's hard to get to a
higher point of view.

00:59:01.181 --> 00:59:03.954
But have you noticed adults
are starting to do that now?

00:59:03.954 --> 00:59:05.370
They're starting
to say, you know,

00:59:05.370 --> 00:59:07.950
even though I might be a little
bit on the side of the center

00:59:07.950 --> 00:59:09.200
line, the people
who are a little bit

00:59:09.200 --> 00:59:11.520
on the other side of the
line make a lot of sense.

00:59:11.520 --> 00:59:13.104
We can have a
conversation about that.

00:59:13.104 --> 00:59:15.061
And finally, I want you
to remember the DeGraff

00:59:15.061 --> 00:59:17.090
hypothesis, which is
probably what they'll

00:59:17.090 --> 00:59:18.610
remember on my tombstone.

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:20.360
Out of all the stuff
I've done in my life,

00:59:20.360 --> 00:59:22.550
the amount of innovation
an organization produces

00:59:22.550 --> 00:59:25.100
is inversely related to the
number of stupid PowerPoint

00:59:25.100 --> 00:59:27.200
slides or elaborate
process diagrams

00:59:27.200 --> 00:59:28.670
it makes about innovation.

00:59:28.670 --> 00:59:32.105
In the old words of Phil
Knight, you just have to do it.

00:59:32.105 --> 00:59:34.730
So I want to take us-- first, I
want to thank you for having us

00:59:34.730 --> 00:59:35.330
here.

00:59:35.330 --> 00:59:38.227
I want to take a second to take
some questions, if we could.

00:59:38.227 --> 00:59:39.560
I know we're a little over time.

00:59:39.560 --> 00:59:41.210
But I want to take
questions because I

00:59:41.210 --> 00:59:47.810
know that this is a very
counter-intuitive view of how

00:59:47.810 --> 00:59:48.650
innovation works.

00:59:48.650 --> 00:59:50.390
And what we didn't
talk about here--

00:59:50.390 --> 00:59:52.250
I took it out of the
slide deck-- is we--

00:59:52.250 --> 00:59:54.770
I did a number of--

00:59:54.770 --> 00:59:57.080
we did a lot of analysis
on the stock market--

00:59:57.080 --> 00:59:59.180
is what it came down
to, starting in 1993,

00:59:59.180 --> 01:00:02.020
more effectively in 2010.

01:00:02.020 --> 01:00:04.430
And we started looking at
these kind of indicators

01:00:04.430 --> 01:00:06.680
for contrarian points of view.

01:00:06.680 --> 01:00:08.570
And what happened with
the organizations that

01:00:08.570 --> 01:00:12.265
had high scores in
these opposite areas--

01:00:12.265 --> 01:00:14.390
it turns out that they
outperformed everybody else.

01:00:14.390 --> 01:00:17.245
And this growth index that
we've talked about that almost

01:00:17.245 --> 01:00:17.870
no one's beat--

01:00:17.870 --> 01:00:19.369
I think we've only
lost to it, like,

01:00:19.369 --> 01:00:21.510
a half a dozen times
over the years.

01:00:21.510 --> 01:00:24.920
So the notion is it's more than
just a typology or a style.

01:00:24.920 --> 01:00:26.810
There's really sort of
an analytical engine

01:00:26.810 --> 01:00:28.065
underneath that.

01:00:28.065 --> 01:00:30.440
So with, that let's take some
questions-- some push-back,

01:00:30.440 --> 01:00:32.060
please?

01:00:32.060 --> 01:00:34.779
AUDIENCE: So here in the office,
we're broken up between floor.

01:00:34.779 --> 01:00:35.570
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yeah.

01:00:35.570 --> 01:00:37.610
AUDIENCE: And those correspond
to the different verticals

01:00:37.610 --> 01:00:38.277
that we support.

01:00:38.277 --> 01:00:39.026
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yep.

01:00:39.026 --> 01:00:40.640
AUDIENCE: I'm across
North America.

01:00:40.640 --> 01:00:42.800
On my floor, there's
a lot of innovation

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:44.720
that happens because we
have a lot of freedom

01:00:44.720 --> 01:00:48.920
to pitch an idea, pitch a
project, and run with it.

01:00:48.920 --> 01:00:53.510
And I'm wondering, given your
hypothesis and the studies

01:00:53.510 --> 01:00:57.890
you've done, how can leaders
or owners of projects

01:00:57.890 --> 01:01:02.390
best identify these
opposite colors to best--

01:01:02.390 --> 01:01:03.980
I guess, to make the best team?

01:01:03.980 --> 01:01:04.771
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yeah.

01:01:04.771 --> 01:01:07.010
I think the easy answer
to that is see what people

01:01:07.010 --> 01:01:09.470
do under stress or duress.

01:01:09.470 --> 01:01:11.975
And that was that kind
of throwaway slide I had.

01:01:11.975 --> 01:01:15.397
But if you've got somebody
who's primarily a sage,

01:01:15.397 --> 01:01:16.730
they're going to be extroverted.

01:01:16.730 --> 01:01:18.530
And they're going to
be highly interactive.

01:01:18.530 --> 01:01:20.030
So when they have
a problem, they're

01:01:20.030 --> 01:01:22.580
going to consult
other people, right?

01:01:22.580 --> 01:01:25.646
When you've got somebody
who's an athlete, when they

01:01:25.646 --> 01:01:27.020
get a problem,
what they'll do is

01:01:27.020 --> 01:01:28.430
they'll shut other people out.

01:01:28.430 --> 01:01:30.170
They're the opposite
of team people.

01:01:30.170 --> 01:01:31.610
They'll take a lot of ownership.

01:01:31.610 --> 01:01:33.680
And they'll get rid of
things in their life.

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:35.590
You'll notice it's
like spring cleaning.

01:01:35.590 --> 01:01:37.650
And they'll focus on
one or two things.

01:01:37.650 --> 01:01:39.590
They're very goal-oriented.

01:01:39.590 --> 01:01:43.220
When you're looking at
somebody who's an engineer,

01:01:43.220 --> 01:01:45.590
they'll want to go back
and look at the data.

01:01:45.590 --> 01:01:47.810
And they'll think
sequentially about the data.

01:01:47.810 --> 01:01:49.670
And they'll think
about sort of combing

01:01:49.670 --> 01:01:52.730
through where the error
was and how to appreciate,

01:01:52.730 --> 01:01:53.660
how to fix the error.

01:01:53.660 --> 01:01:55.784
And if you've got somebody
who's a green, they'll--

01:01:55.784 --> 01:01:58.370
what you'll see them do
is look for escape routes.

01:01:58.370 --> 01:01:59.420
They're kind of wiggly--

01:01:59.420 --> 01:02:01.760
does this make sense-- because
they're very imaginative.

01:02:01.760 --> 01:02:03.930
They know how to tell a
tale in an interesting way.

01:02:03.930 --> 01:02:05.055
And they'll try and escape.

01:02:05.055 --> 01:02:06.950
So when I look at
people, one of the things

01:02:06.950 --> 01:02:08.780
I pay close attention
to is what do people

01:02:08.780 --> 01:02:10.670
do when they're stressed out.

01:02:10.670 --> 01:02:12.149
Does this make sense to you?

01:02:12.149 --> 01:02:14.190
And if you really want to
make things successful,

01:02:14.190 --> 01:02:16.915
I think the big thing is, what
do we constitute as success?

01:02:16.915 --> 01:02:19.610
So one of the things I notice
in places like Google is people,

01:02:19.610 --> 01:02:21.109
when they do a small
experiment, are

01:02:21.109 --> 01:02:24.649
highly successful because
it's very artist organization.

01:02:24.649 --> 01:02:25.940
The real question becomes what?

01:02:25.940 --> 01:02:28.370
How does that make it into
something that's scalable?

01:02:28.370 --> 01:02:29.900
And the irony of Google is what?

01:02:29.900 --> 01:02:32.180
And this is sort of
the hard truth of this.

01:02:32.180 --> 01:02:33.890
You have all these
different businesses.

01:02:33.890 --> 01:02:35.950
How many make money?

01:02:35.950 --> 01:02:37.570
How many of the
businesses make money?

01:02:37.570 --> 01:02:38.840
Is everybody following this?

01:02:38.840 --> 01:02:39.340
Yeah.

01:02:39.340 --> 01:02:40.714
Don't think we
don't know, right?

01:02:40.714 --> 01:02:43.950
And the notion is those are
places that effectively engage

01:02:43.950 --> 01:02:46.260
the reds and the blues, right?

01:02:46.260 --> 01:02:48.660
So there's got to be a place,
and this was the problem

01:02:48.660 --> 01:02:50.405
when I was young in my--

01:02:50.405 --> 01:02:51.780
I was an advisor
to what's called

01:02:51.780 --> 01:02:53.730
applied integrated
systems at Apple.

01:02:53.730 --> 01:02:55.620
The problem with Apple
in the beginning days

01:02:55.620 --> 01:02:57.661
was it was very much like
here, but they couldn't

01:02:57.661 --> 01:02:58.710
figure how to make money.

01:02:58.710 --> 01:03:00.570
They couldn't figure out how
to get quality sorted out.

01:03:00.570 --> 01:03:01.700
Does this make sense?

01:03:01.700 --> 01:03:03.450
So when Jobs came back,
what did he learn?

01:03:03.450 --> 01:03:06.130
He learned how to make money
and get quality sorted out.

01:03:06.130 --> 01:03:07.740
So this is the issue of--

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:08.730
it can be successful.

01:03:08.730 --> 01:03:11.169
But to be successful all
the way through the cycle,

01:03:11.169 --> 01:03:12.960
you have to look for
these different types.

