01:03:45.450 --> 01:03:46.740
They'll go, I'm
insanely great at this.

01:03:46.740 --> 01:03:47.340
Go, great.

01:03:47.340 --> 01:03:48.120
That's great.

01:03:48.120 --> 01:03:49.717
Have someone else pick a card.

01:03:49.717 --> 01:03:50.550
You're the opposite.

01:03:50.550 --> 01:03:50.850
OK.

01:03:50.850 --> 01:03:52.410
The two of you are now
going to work on this.

01:03:52.410 --> 01:03:54.180
Now, here's the challenge,
the real challenge,

01:03:54.180 --> 01:03:56.190
because we do this every
day in the innovation labs,

01:03:56.190 --> 01:03:58.315
some of the biggest
innovations people write about.

01:03:58.315 --> 01:04:00.300
The biggest challenge
is keeping the conflict

01:04:00.300 --> 01:04:01.877
constructive, right?

01:04:01.877 --> 01:04:03.210
And I'll put it to you this way.

01:04:03.210 --> 01:04:05.460
I have what I call big Jeff
days and little Jeff days.

01:04:05.460 --> 01:04:07.747
Big Jeff days, I'm very open
to constructive conflict.

01:04:07.747 --> 01:04:09.580
Little Jeff days-- you
ever get in that mood

01:04:09.580 --> 01:04:12.000
where you're like, oh, god,
I can't deal with this person

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:12.720
today?

01:04:12.720 --> 01:04:14.006
Now-- and I'm not rude.

01:04:14.006 --> 01:04:15.880
And I'm not going to
fight in a negative way.

01:04:15.880 --> 01:04:17.046
I'm just going to disengage.

01:04:17.046 --> 01:04:20.010
I'm going to say,
today, today, there's

01:04:20.010 --> 01:04:21.900
a lot stuff going on in my life.

01:04:21.900 --> 01:04:22.714
And I love you.

01:04:22.714 --> 01:04:23.880
And I want to work with you.

01:04:23.880 --> 01:04:27.050
But today, I'm taking a holiday.

01:04:27.050 --> 01:04:28.570
I'm getting off the grid today.

01:04:28.570 --> 01:04:30.240
So part of it is
knowing to do that.

01:04:30.240 --> 01:04:31.906
I think it's also a
good life skill when

01:04:31.906 --> 01:04:33.899
you have a partner, right?

01:04:33.899 --> 01:04:34.440
Someone else?

01:04:36.987 --> 01:04:37.570
AUDIENCE: Hey.

01:04:37.570 --> 01:04:40.110
So you talked a lot about
the power of tension

01:04:40.110 --> 01:04:42.730
and the creative power
of constructive conflict.

01:04:42.730 --> 01:04:44.790
And I think most
people would agree

01:04:44.790 --> 01:04:47.627
that America is in a
heightened state of tension

01:04:47.627 --> 01:04:48.460
and divide nowadays.

01:04:48.460 --> 01:04:48.770
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yeah.

01:04:48.770 --> 01:04:49.560
It sure is.

01:04:49.560 --> 01:04:52.080
AUDIENCE: So I'm curious
what you would recommend,

01:04:52.080 --> 01:04:55.350
or how can we harness
this tension productively?

01:04:55.350 --> 01:04:58.920
JEFF DEGRAFF: I think it's sort
of the opposite of the bell

01:04:58.920 --> 01:04:59.850
curve.

01:04:59.850 --> 01:05:03.310
I think what's happening
is actually twofold.

01:05:03.310 --> 01:05:05.400
First of all, I
think the conflict

01:05:05.400 --> 01:05:07.890
that we're having is
a conflict that we've

01:05:07.890 --> 01:05:10.500
needed to have since the 1980s.

01:05:10.500 --> 01:05:13.230
And the way I would
characterize the conflict

01:05:13.230 --> 01:05:15.339
is when I looked at the--
before the election,

01:05:15.339 --> 01:05:17.130
I was at one of the
big government agencies

01:05:17.130 --> 01:05:18.237
giving this talk.

01:05:18.237 --> 01:05:19.820
And so I'm not trying
to be political.

01:05:19.820 --> 01:05:22.680
I'm trying to illuminate
something here.

01:05:22.680 --> 01:05:25.110
And I said I thought that
Trump may very well win

01:05:25.110 --> 01:05:26.895
the election, which, of course,
was contrary to what everybody

01:05:26.895 --> 01:05:26.990
said.

01:05:26.990 --> 01:05:27.720
And they said, why?

01:05:27.720 --> 01:05:29.070
And I said, think of bell curve.

01:05:29.070 --> 01:05:32.660
Who got blown out after
the '08 recession?

01:05:32.660 --> 01:05:35.190
There were four groups
that got blown out.

01:05:35.190 --> 01:05:36.810
The first group
were young people.

01:05:36.810 --> 01:05:37.820
You guys got blown out.

01:05:37.820 --> 01:05:38.650
It was bad.

01:05:38.650 --> 01:05:39.870
It was really bad.

01:05:39.870 --> 01:05:42.690
The second was old people
who were on retirement.

01:05:42.690 --> 01:05:44.040
They got blown out.

01:05:44.040 --> 01:05:46.605
And I-- the penny
dropped when I was at a--

01:05:46.605 --> 01:05:50.040
I walked by a Bernie
rally here on campus.

01:05:50.040 --> 01:05:53.940
And I'd never seen young
people with old people before.

01:05:53.940 --> 01:05:55.769
This was like-- and
I pay attention.

01:05:55.769 --> 01:05:57.810
I'm one of those guys who
pays a lot of attention

01:05:57.810 --> 01:06:00.125
to incongruities--
and went, wow.

01:06:00.125 --> 01:06:01.000
Well, think about it.

01:06:01.000 --> 01:06:03.291
Those are two groups that
are one end of the bell curve

01:06:03.291 --> 01:06:04.260
that get blown out.

01:06:04.260 --> 01:06:07.500
The other groups that got
blown out were people of color.

01:06:07.500 --> 01:06:08.100
All right.

01:06:08.100 --> 01:06:11.460
Think about all the groups
in the United States.

01:06:11.460 --> 01:06:13.680
And a lot of those
groups didn't vote.

01:06:13.680 --> 01:06:15.360
They disengaged, right?

01:06:15.360 --> 01:06:16.610
Look at the numbers.

01:06:16.610 --> 01:06:18.687
And then I need you
to think about people

01:06:18.687 --> 01:06:20.520
who look like me, who
are from neighborhoods

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:22.170
like where I'm from.

01:06:22.170 --> 01:06:24.810
And they've been downwardly
mobile since about '83.

01:06:24.810 --> 01:06:27.350
And the notion is their
real economic power,

01:06:27.350 --> 01:06:29.640
their lack of education,
their mortality rate--

01:06:29.640 --> 01:06:32.070
look at anything right
now in those numbers.

01:06:32.070 --> 01:06:33.540
And they were really mad.

01:06:33.540 --> 01:06:37.436
Out of all of those groups,
only one of them voted.

01:06:37.436 --> 01:06:38.310
Does this make sense?

01:06:38.310 --> 01:06:40.650
And they voted big, right?

01:06:40.650 --> 01:06:43.800
So when we start looking at
the numbers, what I looked at

01:06:43.800 --> 01:06:46.377
was who's actually
going to act, which

01:06:46.377 --> 01:06:47.460
is an innovation question.

01:06:47.460 --> 01:06:48.330
Is this making sense to you?

01:06:48.330 --> 01:06:48.760
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:06:48.760 --> 01:06:50.135
JEFF DEGRAFF: So
now the opposite

01:06:50.135 --> 01:06:51.760
of that is how this
will come together

01:06:51.760 --> 01:06:54.070
is you start looking at the
middle of the bell curve.

01:06:54.070 --> 01:06:55.480
And you draw a line.

01:06:55.480 --> 01:06:57.090
What's happening is
reasonable people,

01:06:57.090 --> 01:06:59.550
which constitute about
the 80% of the middle,

01:06:59.550 --> 01:07:01.080
are starting to
talk to each other.

01:07:01.080 --> 01:07:02.996
So you think about being
in a business school,

01:07:02.996 --> 01:07:05.220
business school's filled
with a lot of University

01:07:05.220 --> 01:07:07.410
of Chicago people,
very conservative--

01:07:07.410 --> 01:07:09.660
they read "The Economist"
every day and the "Journal."

01:07:09.660 --> 01:07:11.340
It's a little right for me.

01:07:11.340 --> 01:07:13.260
And then there's other
people in the school--

01:07:13.260 --> 01:07:15.690
read "The Times"
every day, "Bloomberg"

01:07:15.690 --> 01:07:17.130
every day-- a little left.

01:07:17.130 --> 01:07:18.040
I read the "Post."

01:07:18.040 --> 01:07:19.040
I'm kind of a down the--

01:07:19.040 --> 01:07:21.464
I'm sort of that
guy, down the middle.

01:07:21.464 --> 01:07:23.130
But the notion is
you're starting to see

01:07:23.130 --> 01:07:25.319
those people come together.

01:07:25.319 --> 01:07:27.110
The majority-- is this
making sense to you?

01:07:27.110 --> 01:07:27.360
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:07:27.360 --> 01:07:28.410
JEFF DEGRAFF: And
they're starting to say,

01:07:28.410 --> 01:07:30.270
we're going to have to take
care of some of these things

01:07:30.270 --> 01:07:31.980
that we haven't taken care of.

01:07:31.980 --> 01:07:34.260
So there are issues of--
there are social issues.

01:07:34.260 --> 01:07:35.530
And there are economic issues.

01:07:35.530 --> 01:07:37.000
And both of those issues--

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:39.970
I believe what you're starting
to see is that come together.

01:07:39.970 --> 01:07:41.800
I think what'll
happen is this will

01:07:41.800 --> 01:07:45.850
be horribly painful for the
next 18 months for both sides.

01:07:45.850 --> 01:07:47.350
Nobody's going to win this.

01:07:47.350 --> 01:07:49.442
But it's a kitchen.

01:07:49.442 --> 01:07:51.400
It should have started
as a kitchen discussion.

01:07:51.400 --> 01:07:53.920
And it's now a fight that's
kind of calming down.

01:07:53.920 --> 01:07:56.470
That's my interpretation
of what's happening.

01:07:56.470 --> 01:07:59.320
And I think at the end
of this, and that this

01:07:59.320 --> 01:08:02.890
is-- because remember, conflict,
even if it's not constructive,

01:08:02.890 --> 01:08:05.080
will often result in innovation.

01:08:05.080 --> 01:08:08.070
I think we will have
to get to a new place.

01:08:08.070 --> 01:08:09.417
Is everybody following this?

01:08:09.417 --> 01:08:10.250
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:08:10.250 --> 01:08:12.010
JEFF DEGRAFF: So
that's my take on it.

01:08:12.010 --> 01:08:15.840
But I can imagine being young
and seeing this rinkside.

01:08:15.840 --> 01:08:19.660
It's not any-- and it's--

01:08:19.660 --> 01:08:22.450
when people compare this to--

01:08:22.450 --> 01:08:26.939
just drop the comparisons
to Hitler or to Watergate.

01:08:26.939 --> 01:08:28.930
This is a whole
different animal.

01:08:28.930 --> 01:08:32.109
And I think a lot of those
metaphors or analogies are--

01:08:32.109 --> 01:08:33.036
don't work.

01:08:33.036 --> 01:08:34.660
I think we're looking
at a world that's

01:08:34.660 --> 01:08:36.830
connected both vertically
and horizontally.

01:08:36.830 --> 01:08:38.979
And I think the horizontal
connections are so much

01:08:38.979 --> 01:08:40.210
stronger in your generation.

01:08:40.210 --> 01:08:42.120
I think it's going
to be very different.

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:43.460
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

01:08:43.460 --> 01:08:44.543
JEFF DEGRAFF: Anyone else?

01:08:47.410 --> 01:08:48.390
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:08:48.390 --> 01:08:51.630
What's your perspective
on the historical cycles

01:08:51.630 --> 01:08:53.939
of innovation?

01:08:53.939 --> 01:08:57.450
Even in terms of nostalgia,
as an example, this year,

01:08:57.450 --> 01:09:01.170
with all this turmoil, people
are looking back to the 1980s,

01:09:01.170 --> 01:09:02.410
things like that.

01:09:02.410 --> 01:09:02.660
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yeah.

01:09:02.660 --> 01:09:04.210
AUDIENCE: What do you think
about as the decade's best?

01:09:04.210 --> 01:09:04.380
JEFF DEGRAFF: Yeah.

01:09:04.380 --> 01:09:06.510
I'd like to say that I
don't think they exist,

01:09:06.510 --> 01:09:09.850
but I do think they exist.

01:09:09.850 --> 01:09:13.080
Here's-- there's a very
famous book written at the end

01:09:13.080 --> 01:09:17.563
of the 1800s by Oswald Spengler.

01:09:17.563 --> 01:09:19.229
And Spengler basically--
it's a-- book's

01:09:19.229 --> 01:09:21.120
called "The Decline
of the West."

01:09:21.120 --> 01:09:24.630
And Spengler is this German
academic who basically gets it.

01:09:24.630 --> 01:09:27.449
He's really-- he starts
showing what's going to happen.

01:09:27.449 --> 01:09:29.490
And what's amazing is he
predicts the First World

01:09:29.490 --> 01:09:31.050
War and the Second World War.

01:09:31.050 --> 01:09:33.000
And the reason he predicts them
is he understands the cycle.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:34.200
So he's looking at cycles.

01:09:34.200 --> 01:09:36.930
And economies happen in cycles.

01:09:36.930 --> 01:09:39.510
So the part that I
would say I disagree

01:09:39.510 --> 01:09:42.210
is that we're in a very
different accelerated age

01:09:42.210 --> 01:09:45.390
with all of this horizontal,
what I call longitude,

01:09:45.390 --> 01:09:49.170
connection, the network world,
Niall Ferguson's new book,

01:09:49.170 --> 01:09:51.609
"The Square and the
Tower," that stuff.

01:09:51.609 --> 01:09:53.876
And I think that's true,
at least to some degree.

01:09:53.876 --> 01:09:55.500
I think the other--
but the other thing

01:09:55.500 --> 01:09:57.160
is human nature's human nature.

01:09:57.160 --> 01:10:01.700
And what happens in human nature
is you develop a theory of--

01:10:01.700 --> 01:10:03.510
a new theory of governance.

01:10:03.510 --> 01:10:08.280
And over time, that theory
decays into the very thing

01:10:08.280 --> 01:10:09.120
it tried not to do.

01:10:09.120 --> 01:10:10.590
This is what Weber wrote about.

01:10:10.590 --> 01:10:13.207
"Nineteen Eighty-Four"-- this
is what Orwell wrote about.

01:10:13.207 --> 01:10:14.790
The animals are all
going to be equal.

01:10:14.790 --> 01:10:16.770
And then they become
Stalinist, right?

01:10:16.770 --> 01:10:18.030
Does this make sense to you?

01:10:18.030 --> 01:10:21.360
So yes, I think there
is something to cycles.

01:10:21.360 --> 01:10:22.980
I think predicting--
when people start

01:10:22.980 --> 01:10:24.900
predicting how many years
they're going to be,

01:10:24.900 --> 01:10:27.450
like the Russians do, or
how big they're going to be,

01:10:27.450 --> 01:10:29.460
then I think it
gets a little iffy.

01:10:29.460 --> 01:10:31.140
Am I making sense?

01:10:31.140 --> 01:10:35.020
So in summary, yes, I
think there are cycles.

01:10:35.020 --> 01:10:37.260
But I think the cycles are
a little less predictive

01:10:37.260 --> 01:10:38.520
than people think they are.

01:10:38.520 --> 01:10:40.230
Did I answer your question?

01:10:40.230 --> 01:10:40.990
What do you think?

01:10:40.990 --> 01:10:41.970
That's my question.

01:10:41.970 --> 01:10:43.500
What do you think?

01:10:43.500 --> 01:10:45.810
AUDIENCE: I think that
when innovation happens,

01:10:45.810 --> 01:10:49.710
for a few years, people accept
that all this change happened

01:10:49.710 --> 01:10:52.620
and then maybe calm
down for a few years

01:10:52.620 --> 01:10:54.990
because they're riding the
wave of the changes that

01:10:54.990 --> 01:10:57.660
took place, technology birth.

01:10:57.660 --> 01:10:59.580
JEFF DEGRAFF: Did you read--

01:10:59.580 --> 01:11:00.960
the woman's name is Jackson.

01:11:00.960 --> 01:11:06.030
She's the president of
Rensselaer Polytechnic.

01:11:06.030 --> 01:11:08.700
Did you read her book
on innovation cycles?

01:11:08.700 --> 01:11:10.200
She basically
points something out

01:11:10.200 --> 01:11:12.330
that I think is very damning.

01:11:12.330 --> 01:11:15.180
She said that most of the
wave, which your company was

01:11:15.180 --> 01:11:17.070
built on, was--

01:11:17.070 --> 01:11:20.310
sort of ended in the mid-'90s,
and that what we've been doing

01:11:20.310 --> 01:11:23.165
is iterations of that
wave for a long time.

01:11:23.165 --> 01:11:24.540
And I know that
when people start

01:11:24.540 --> 01:11:27.240
talking about collaborative,
open, innovation networks--

01:11:27.240 --> 01:11:29.940
I worked on Apple Net,
which became iTunes.

01:11:29.940 --> 01:11:32.710
That's, what, '84, '85, right?

01:11:32.710 --> 01:11:35.730
You start thinking about what
people talk about is now.

01:11:35.730 --> 01:11:38.700
The Innovatrium was built
10 years before WeWork.

01:11:38.700 --> 01:11:41.010
So the notion is when
you start looking

01:11:41.010 --> 01:11:43.810
at where the genesis of things
are and you-- particularly, you

01:11:43.810 --> 01:11:45.060
know where this is really fun?

01:11:45.060 --> 01:11:46.710
Music, right?

01:11:46.710 --> 01:11:48.350
I grew up in the '70s.

01:11:48.350 --> 01:11:50.130
I went to high
school in the '70s.

01:11:50.130 --> 01:11:52.327
And people say,
well, what happened?

01:11:52.327 --> 01:11:54.660
You give all the music genres
that people listen to now.

01:11:54.660 --> 01:11:56.076
And they all
happened in the '70s.

01:11:56.076 --> 01:11:57.300
Is this making sense to you?

01:11:57.300 --> 01:11:59.400
So the '90s-- the
'90s for technology,

01:11:59.400 --> 01:12:02.520
'70s for music-- the issue
becomes, at what point is

01:12:02.520 --> 01:12:05.010
that long cycle done, right?

01:12:05.010 --> 01:12:07.050
And usually, it has to
be disrupted to be done.

01:12:07.050 --> 01:12:09.072
But you're-- I think
you're seeing disruption.

01:12:09.072 --> 01:12:10.530
I come back to what
I talked about.

01:12:10.530 --> 01:12:11.946
Maybe you weren't
in the room-- we

01:12:11.946 --> 01:12:14.280
were talking about
disruption of institutions.

01:12:14.280 --> 01:12:15.630
Marriage is different now.

01:12:15.630 --> 01:12:17.520
Religion is different now.

01:12:17.520 --> 01:12:18.900
What work is is different now.

01:12:18.900 --> 01:12:20.820
Universities will
soon be different now.

01:12:20.820 --> 01:12:21.780
Trust me, they will.

01:12:21.780 --> 01:12:23.530
Medicine will be different now.

01:12:23.530 --> 01:12:26.625
And I think those are
more subtle long cycles.

01:12:26.625 --> 01:12:27.420
Anyone else?

01:12:29.980 --> 01:12:31.980
One more.

01:12:31.980 --> 01:12:33.480
AUDIENCE: Kind of
going back to what

01:12:33.480 --> 01:12:36.300
you're talking about with
contrarian indicators

01:12:36.300 --> 01:12:38.880
and how you saw that these
companies far outperformed

01:12:38.880 --> 01:12:41.610
any others, I was wondering
if you any insight as to how

01:12:41.610 --> 01:12:44.400
we can distill that down and
take that back to our teams,

01:12:44.400 --> 01:12:45.897
put that to work for us?

01:12:45.897 --> 01:12:47.730
JEFF DEGRAFF: I think
what I would recommend

01:12:47.730 --> 01:12:49.620
is I'd read the book, right?

01:12:49.620 --> 01:12:53.670
And I'd say one of the things
that the book will give you

01:12:53.670 --> 01:12:54.572
clues about--

01:12:54.572 --> 01:12:56.280
some of this-- obviously,
I can't open up

01:12:56.280 --> 01:12:57.780
the whole can of worms here.

01:12:57.780 --> 01:12:59.550
So I don't want
over-commit to something.

01:12:59.550 --> 01:13:02.940
But you'll notice that there
are a list of attributes that

01:13:02.940 --> 01:13:05.430
could easily be turned
into key indicators

01:13:05.430 --> 01:13:06.522
that you could follow.

01:13:06.522 --> 01:13:08.730
And then I'd ask you to do
some of your own research,

01:13:08.730 --> 01:13:10.830
to saying if you get some
of these contrarian key

01:13:10.830 --> 01:13:13.410
indicators, and I think in--

01:13:13.410 --> 01:13:13.950
pardon?

01:13:13.950 --> 01:13:14.783
Can you answer that?

01:13:14.783 --> 01:13:16.329
Yeah.

01:13:16.329 --> 01:13:17.120
STANEY DEGRAFF: OK.

